(221, 3, '2012-06-08 15:39:43', '2012-06-08 15:39:43', 'After our 4th overnight flight in 6 days, we arrived in Bangkok to meet up with Adam''s friend, Kasey.  From the airport we sped past imposing skyscrapers and sprawling apartment complexes (occasionally dotted with an imposing Buddha statue or temple).  There was no filth, chaos, or disarray to be seen.  Manicured and high tech, Bangkok presents itself to the world. \n\nAnd so we arrived in the backpacker''s ghetto, Khao San. Every business in this area is catered to tourists: massage parlors, restaurants, bars, clubs, hotels, internet cafes, shopping centers, coffee shops.  Everything is open.  You are invited (nay, commanded) in everywhere.  Bright multi-colored lights twinkle,  loud reggae or lady gaga blares from every speaker,  every ten feet a big neon sign announces drink specials, tours, or sex shows. loose fitting tank tops and tight t-shirts with drawings of bicycles and vintage cameras, screen prints of kubrick''s "full metal jacket", or of a naked woman snorting coke which forms the letters of "facebook", even banksey prints, spill over into the road.  Ironic and aloof - straight from an urban outfitter''s catalogue.  meanwhile, hordes of young, attractive, scantily clad westerners roam aimlessly drinking and eating, buying, smoking, nursing hang-overs, and hitting on one another.  \n\nFrom this angle, it appears that bangkok not only thrives on tourism - tourists are bangkok .  Indeed, Thais do not appear to be consuming Bangkok at all - their only role here is of purveyors of food, booze, massages, whatever you need... Strange to visit a place where the people remain invisible. \n\nTourists gather together in bars and cafes, swapping stories of how they''ve been scammed, rolling their eyes, sighing -- "ugh. thailand!".  An open hostility between tourists and thais is palpable.  A sign in our hostel says "We do not allow Thai people to go upstairs.  No matter the reason".  Not only are the tourists convinced that Thais are scammers, hustlers, and thieves, apparently so is the Thai management (or at least they are complicit in perpetuating this image).  There is something repulsive about the tourist who comes to visit a country only to fear and desire containment from it''s population.  \n\nOne problem with a place like this is that when we are surrounded by people who are just like us, we forget that maybe the rules ought to change a bit, we forget that we are playing on someone else''s field.  And so, the question remains, what is the point of traveling? Why do we spend thousands of dollars to fly across oceans when we only want to replicate home? an inherent ambivalence of the human spirit, the desire to see, feel, touch and taste what lies beyond, and yet the (understandable) desire to stay where we are comfortable?\n\nBut, walk a mile from this place, and the white faces, short shorts, and enormous backpacks begin to disappear, replaced by a bustling city, grocery stores, and old women who bow to greet one another .  Alas! There is a real city beyond the neon glare!  \n\nYesterday we explored the residential streets, local markets, and public spaces of Thai bangkok.  We stumbled across hundreds of tents in front of the parliament building.  In celebration of the day of Vesak, Buddha''s 2,600th year from attaining enlightenment, a group had gathered to cook and share free food for everyone.  Rather than being met as outsiders, the people invited us to join, took us from stall to stall, encouraging us to share a meal.  Old women tugged me from one place to another, filling my arms with rambutan (a red fruit native to here covered in spikes and filled with a lychee-like jelly), popcorn, noodles, and bananas.  There was a large stage where people spoke, danced, and sung.  Big bags of rice and other food staples were being handed out for free to those in need.    \n\nAnd so, with our faiths somewhat restored, we headed back to the neon, and yes, ended the night with a $3 foot massage.  \n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120608-093711.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120608-093711.jpg" alt="20120608-093711.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153605.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153605.jpg" alt="20120626-153605.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'bangkok: the cancun of southeast asia', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bangkok-the-cancun-of-southeast-asia', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:36:25', '2012-06-26 07:36:25', '', 0, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=221', 0, 'post', '', 2),
