(243, 3, '2012-06-13 06:12:44', '2012-06-13 06:12:44', 'Sunday evening we hopped on an overnight bus north to Bagan, a region in central Myanmar speckled with over 4000 ancient Buddhist temples.  In the morning we rented cheap single speed cruisers and headed toward the largest and most impressive of these structures.  While most of the temples we passed were just large enough to house a single 15 foot tall sitting Buddha statue and a handful of admirers, others towered nearly 200 feet above Bagan''s low-lying shrubbery.  The temples, all built between 1057 and 1287 A.D., still appeared to be active places of worship for the people ofBagan.  In front of many of the stupas, women sold wreaths of orange blossoms and other flowers which local people placed as offerings in front of the serene Buddhas.  The temples themselves were plain and worn, ungracefully showing their age.  The Buddha statues housed in most were nearly identical: legs crossed with a mysterious half-smile.  We spent most of the day hopping from temple to temple, ducking inside just long enough to escape the oppressive mid-day sun and discover that, yes, this buddha does indeed look just like the last.  While the temples'' interiors were mostly unremarkable, contrasted against the sun scorched terrain, their silhouettes seemed almost alien.  It wasn''t until we climbed to the top of one of the taller pagodas and looked far across the landscape below that I finally felt a sense of awe.  Holy cow.  There really are thousands of these things.', '24 hours in Bagan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '230-revision-3', '', '', '2012-06-13 06:12:44', '2012-06-13 06:12:44', '', 230, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=243', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
