(282, 2, '2012-06-13 06:17:13', '2012-06-13 06:17:13', 'We arrived early Saturday morning, unprepared for what was in store.  The airport was tiny, reflecting the 17 year-long tourism boycott which ended only two years ago.  At the airport we were met by men wearing longyi --long traditional skirts, and women whose entire faces were painted yellow.  Initially I thought it was for the benefit of tourists, a kitschy show of traditional culture. Turns out, unlike most countries where men wear western clothing while women are the carriers of culture, in Myanmar it is the men who wear traditional clothing while women dress in imported Chinese blouses and skirts.  The women, however, don''t pass as entirely western.  Women and children paint large circles, intricate lines, or entire masks of  tha nap khar, a yellowish paste made from wood, on their faces.  \n\nWe soon discovered that Myanmar does not accept cards.  No one.  No where. None whatsoever.  One must exchange precious US dollars.  And not just any dollars. Myanmar does not accept bills more than six years old, torn, worn, folded, or otherwise show any sign of use.  Myanmar apparently also has a delusional conception of their currency''s worth.  At the airport, government registered money changers offer an exchange rate of $1 USD for 8 Kyat, while just outside the airport doors the "black-market" offers 840 Kyat for $1 USD.   So, we scrounged together whatever we had, using heavy books and moist towels in a true mafioso fashion to turn our crumpled, old dollars into something acceptable to the street-corner, back-door money changers.   Alas.  We largely failed.  \n\nIn our two days in Yangon, we could count all the westerners we saw on our fingers.  Due to the bad international press, heavy travel restrictions, and difficulty obtaining a visa, only the most intrepid travelers, or those anxious to escape the heavily trodden backpacker circuit of southeast asia, make their way to Myanmar.  Billboards dot the country which read "Myanmar welcomes and takes care of tourists".  This is a message that the people have truly taken to heart.    There is little to no haggling on price.  We never felt taken advantage of, preyed upon, extorted or otherwise abused here. While I risk making absurd generalizations that no population could live up to, our impression was  that Burmese people are open, honest, generous with their time, and curious about us.  Every person we passed greeted us with a wave and a large smile, little kids ran up to dole out high fives, and mothers encouraged their toddlers to blow kisses at us.  Really a refreshing change of pace for the calloused traveler, always on guard, always cynical.  \n\nWe could also count all of the overt signs of a military presence: Zero. For a country known internationally for a military that abuses, rapes, murders, silences, and systematically strips away rights from its people, the strong arm of the state was illusive. Most shops openly posted photographs of Aung San Suu Kyi, who, likened to Nelson Mandela and having received the Nobel Peace Prize,  is a national hero and represents hope for political reform.  We even witnessed a protest.  At Shwedagon Paya, a large (and astoundingly beautiful) temple complex in the center of the city, Buddhist monks (who have historically been loud and visible in their dissent against the government) and lay people from Rakhin state condemned the government for not protecting its people from politically and religiously motivated acts of violence (allegedly) committed by Bangladeshis on the two nations'' border.   \n\nAlong with being on the front line for political reform, monks, clad in flowing red robes, continued to shatter our preconceptions of serene, docile, and otherworldly beings.  In Myanmar,which is described as the most devout Buddhist country in the world, all boys and men are expected to shave their heads, don robes, and pick up alms bowls at least twice in their lives, once in boyhood, and once after becoming a man.  As a result, the line between monks and lay people is fuzzy.  Many monks smoke cigarettes, are covered in tattoos, and spend their days watching soccer and eating snacks with their buddies.  It took us a long time to become accustomed to the sight of a monk reclining at a street-side cafe, eating peanuts and giggling with friends.    Yes, perhaps I could be a monk when I grow up...\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-124624.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-124624.jpg" alt="20120613-124624.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Hello Burma! Or should I call you Myanmar?...', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '228-revision-3', '', '', '2012-06-13 06:17:13', '2012-06-13 06:17:13', '', 228, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=282', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(283, 3, '2012-06-13 06:19:58', '2012-06-13 06:19:58', ' ', '24 hours in Bagan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '239-revision-2', '', '', '2012-06-13 06:19:58', '2012-06-13 06:19:58', '', 239, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=283', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(284, 2, '2012-06-08 14:39:43', '2012-06-08 14:39:43', 'After our 4th overnight flight in 6 days, we arrived in Bangkok to meet up with Adam''s friend, Kasey.  From the airport we sped past imposing skyscrapers and sprawling apartment complexes (occasionally dotted with an imposing Buddha statue or temple).  There was no filth, chaos, or disarray to be seen.  Manicured and high tech, Bangkok presents itself to the world. \n\nAnd so we arrived in the backpacker''s ghetto, Khao San. Every business in this area is catered to tourists: massage parlors, restaurants, bars, clubs, hotels, internet cafes, shopping centers, coffee shops.  Everything is open.  You are invited (nay, commanded) in everywhere.  Bright multi-colored lights twinkle,  loud reggae or lady gaga blares from every speaker,  every ten feet a big neon sign announces drink specials, tours, or sex shows. loose fitting tank tops and tight t-shirts with drawings of bicycles and vintage cameras, screen prints of kubrick''s "full metal jacket", or of a naked woman snorting coke which forms the letters of "facebook", even banksey prints, spill over into the road.  Ironic and aloof - straight from an urban outfitter''s catalogue.  meanwhile, hordes of young, attractive, scantily clad westerners roam aimlessly drinking and eating, buying, smoking, nursing hang-overs, and hitting on one another.  \n\nFrom this angle, it appears that bangkok not only thrives on tourism - tourists are bangkok .  Indeed, Thais do not appear to be consuming Bangkok at all - their only role here is of purveyors of food, booze, massages, whatever you need... Strange to visit a place where the people remain invisible. \n\nTourists gather together in bars and cafes, swapping stories of how they''ve been scammed, rolling their eyes, sighing -- "ugh. thailand!".  An open hostility between tourists and thais is palpable.  A sign in our hostel says "We do not allow Thai people to go upstairs.  No matter the reason".  Not only are the tourists convinced that Thais are scammers, hustlers, and thieves, apparently so is the Thai management (or at least they are complicit in perpetuating this image).  There is something repulsive about the tourist who comes to visit a country only to fear and desire containment from it''s population.  \n\nOne problem with a place like this is that when we are surrounded by people who are just like us, we forget that maybe the rules ought to change a bit, we forget that we are playing on someone else''s field.  And so, the question remains, what is the point of traveling? Why do we spend thousands of dollars to fly across oceans when we only want to replicate home? an inherent ambivalence of the human spirit, the desire to see, feel, touch and taste what lies beyond, and yet the (understandable) desire to stay where we are comfortable?\n\nBut, walk a mile from this place, and the white faces, short shorts, and enormous backpacks begin to disappear, replaced by a bustling city, grocery stores, and old women who bow to greet one another .  Alas! There is a real city beyond the neon glare!  \n\nYesterday we explored the residential streets, local markets, and public spaces of Thai bangkok.  We stumbled across hundreds of tents in front of the parliament building.  In celebration of the day of Vesak, Buddha''s 2,600th year from attaining enlightenment, a group had gathered to cook and share free food for everyone.  Rather than being met as outsiders, the people invited us to join, took us from stall to stall, encouraging us to share a meal.  Old women tugged me from one place to another, filling my arms with rambutan (a red fruit native to here covered in spikes and filled with a lychee-like jelly), popcorn, noodles, and bananas.  There was a large stage where people spoke, danced, and sung.  Big bags of rice and other food staples were being handed out for free to those in need.    \n\nAnd so, with our faiths somewhat restored, we headed back to the neon, and yes, ended the night with a $3 foot massage.  \n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120608-093711.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120608-093711.jpg" alt="20120608-093711.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'bangkok: the cancun of southeast asia', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '221-revision-2', '', '', '2012-06-08 14:39:43', '2012-06-08 14:39:43', '', 221, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=284', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(286, 2, '2012-06-19 14:57:15', '2012-06-19 14:57:15', 'An early morning bus transported us from the dry flat plains of Bagan through winding roads that seemed to go more up than forward to the cool, misty, mountain top village of Kalaw.  Once there we made arrangements with a local guide, a native of Burma named Toto (we make no attempts at correct spelling of names here), to take us by foot the rest of the way to Inle Lake, our final destination for our tour of Burma.  After a full day in Kalaw of recovering from long bus rides and the sun drenched day of cycling in Bagan, we donned ponchos and started our three day trek early Thursday morning.  By mid morning the rain had cleared and we found ourselves on an uphill march through red mud beneath a canopy of trees.  Aside from frequent stops to pluck leaches from our arms and legs, the morning hike was beautiful, reminiscent of southern Appalachia''s Smokey Mountains or the Cloud Forests of Costa Rica.  By lunch time (or 2 hours after lunch time by Ali''s watch) we''d walked upward until there was no more up to go and stopped for lunch at a Nepalese family''s house which Toto aptly called "the Viewpoint".\n\nDuring the reminder of the day we walked through small villages nestled on hillsides and past the rectangular ponds created by terraced rice paddies while quickly becoming soaked by the afternoons frequent and relentless downpours.  We arrived at a small village cursing our saturated socks and mud-caked shoes just as it started getting dark and were welcomed with a hot fire, a warm meal, and blankets and pillows laid out on the floor of the unadorned, unfurnished main room of a local family''s home.  The three of us (Ali, Kasey, and I) sat on the floor and tore into enough mouth-watering food to feed 12.  We finished dinner around 8 pm, and I pulled out a deck of cards suggesting a game of Hearts.  Kasey and Ali looked at each other and in agreement proposed an alternate plan.  "I''d be ok with just going to bed."\n\nWe woke with the roosters (but somehow after Toto and our host and chef, Johay) and were met with a breakfast equal in enormity and deliciousness to the previous evening''s dinner.   Let me be frank.  Burmese food is not, in general, good.  There''s a reason you don''t find many Burmese restaurants outside of Burma. What we had in Yangon, Bagan, and Kalaw was either very fried, very oily, or often both.  But Johay''s meals shook the foundation of all I had come to know about Burmese cuisine over the previous week.  So it was with mixed emotions that we took the news that Toto would be unable to accompany us for the remainding two days to Inle due to a prior foot injury exacerbated by the previous day''s hike, and that Johay would take us the rest of the way.  While much less talkative than Toto (Johay knew only a few words of English), Johay proved an excellent guide cutting through the beautiful rolling hills of Burmese farmlands plowed by oxen and harvested by hand.  We were blessed with a day of clouds, mist, and no rain.  Late in the afternoon, gesturing with our hands and with exhausted expressions we asked Johay how much further we would walk that day.  He pointed to a pagoda on a mountain far in the distance.  It was time for a quick rest.\n\nWe reached a monastery equipped with thin sleeping mats and thick blankets an hour before sunset.  We washed as well as we could and started a game of cards while Johay disappeared.  Two hours later he miraculously reappeared with two platters full of food.  Where did this food come from?  Had Johay been carrying it in his backpack this whole time?  Our questions were answered when we headed out early the next morning and noticed that Johay''s pack had shrunk to a third of its previous day''s size.\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234615.jpg" alt="20120619-234615.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234608.jpg" alt="20120619-234608.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154150.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154150.jpg" alt="20120626-154150.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'beautiful, bloodsucking burma: trekking from Kalaw to Inle Lake', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-beautiful-bloodsucking-and-bizarre-of-burma-trekking-from-kalaw-to-inle-lake', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:42:07', '2012-06-26 07:42:07', '', 0, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=286', 0, 'post', '', 2),
