(288, 3, '2012-06-13 06:56:05', '2012-06-13 06:56:05', 'Sunday evening we hopped on an overnight bus north to Bagan, a region in central Myanmar speckled with over 4000 ancient Buddhist temples.  In the morning we rented cheap single speed cruisers and headed toward the largest and most impressive of these structures.  While most of the temples we passed were just large enough to house a single 15 foot tall sitting Buddha statue and a handful of admirers, others towered nearly 200 feet above Bagan''s low-lying shrubbery.  The temples, all built between 1057 and 1287 A.D., still appeared to be active places of worship for the people ofBagan.  In front of many of the stupas, women sold wreaths of orange blossoms and other flowers which local people placed as offerings in front of the serene Buddhas.  The temples themselves were plain and worn, ungracefully showing their age.  The Buddha statues housed in most were nearly identical: legs crossed with a mysterious half-smile.  We spent most of the day hopping from temple to temple, ducking inside just long enough to escape the oppressive mid-day sun and discover that, yes, this buddha does indeed look just like the last.  While the temples'' interiors were mostly unremarkable, contrasted against the sun scorched terrain, their silhouettes seemed almost alien.  It wasn''t until we climbed to the top of one of the taller pagodas and looked far across the landscape below that I finally felt a sense of awe.  Holy cow.  There really are thousands of these things.<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=239"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-125110.jpg" alt="20120613-125110.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', '24 hours in Bagan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '230-revision-5', '', '', '2012-06-13 06:56:05', '2012-06-13 06:56:05', '', 230, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=288', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(289, 3, '2012-06-19 15:06:26', '2012-06-19 15:06:26', 'Our final day of trekking was relatively easy.  Most of the day we spent walking along paths.  There wasn''t a leach in sight.  And, instead of rain, we had sun.  And we had a lot of it.\n\nFried to a crisp and exhausted to the bone, like the counterparts to sailors adrift at sea, we were delighted to finally see water by mid-day.  We arrived to a small town on the southern tip of Inle lake and arranged for a long boat taxi to take us around the 7 x 13 mile lake and eventually to Nyaungshwe, the main city on the northern border of Inle.  The people of Inle have adapted to their environment stunningly.  Three miles from any dry land, entire towns exist 15 ft above the water''s surface, jutting up from thousands of bamboo stilts.  Dug-out canoes taxi people from one neighborhood to another and gardens of fruits and vegetables made buoyant from lake weeds and bamboo provide abundant harvests.  Men here have perfected a one legged, one armed row which enables them to stand at the bow of the canoe, wrap their leg around the oar, and steer clear of the lake''s lush vegetation.  \n\nOur first stop was a traditional umbrella workshop.  Three teenage girls greeted our canoe at the dock and demonstrated the step-by-step process of making paper with mulberry tree fiber and carving wood pieces to construct traditional umbrellas used for shade.  They then brought us into their shop, where we were encouraged to look around and buy useless knick-knacks or hand-woven textiles.  "Buy a scarf? A necklace? Look! Woman with long neck!".  In the back corner of the floating shop, presented on a small dais in between stacked sodas and Buddha statues, was a woman of the Padaung ethnic minority - people notorious for elongating their necks with stacks of brass coils.  The sight was somewhat shocking - but not at all because of the woman''s neck - in the back corner of the store tourism and curiosity about cultural difference worked in an internecine fashion to produce a sort of human zoo.  a carnivalesque freak show.  Next to her two Padaung girls with significantly fewer brass rings sat docilely.  I felt complicit in the exploitation and commoditization of other human beings just by being there.  just by looking. And yet, I was interested.  Clearly curiosity isn''t always morally neutral...  \n\nNext we were shuttled to a silver and goldsmith shop.  A woman walked us from station to station, showing us the process of transforming ore into beautifully crafted intricate jewelry.  Another floating workshop demonstrated traditional weaving techniques using thread made from lotus plants.  Then to a local cigar making "workshop" (read: a woman''s living room) where tobacco, brown sugar and other herbs were rolled together in a banana leaf. \n\nWe visited a large, golden pagoda.  In the center, worshipers bowed to 5 amorphous golden blobs.  Apparently, one hundred years ago (according to local lore), these golden Mr. Potato Heads were in the likeness of Buddha.  But, thousands of sheets of gold leaf, applied dutifully by both devotees and waywards looking to store up some good karma for a rainy day, have given these Buddhas some extra curves. \n\nWe also stopped at a very strange monastery where the monks are famed to have taught cats to literally jump through hoops.  And jump they did.  Finally solves the ever present question of ''what do monks do all day?''\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=324"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-231130.jpg" alt="20120619-231130.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'How monks pass the time.', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'long-necks-cat-filled-hoops-and-stilted-villages', '', '\nhttp://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=324', '2012-06-19 16:49:25', '2012-06-19 16:49:25', '', 0, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=289', 0, 'post', '', 1),
