(312, 3, '2012-06-19 15:06:26', '2012-06-19 15:06:26', 'Fried to a crisp and exhausted to the bone, like the counterparts to sailors adrift at sea, we were delighted to finally see water.  We arrived to a small town on the southern tip of Inle lake and arranged for a long boat taxi to take us around the 7 x 13 mile lake and eventually to Nyaungshwe, the main city on the northern border of Inle.  The people of Inle have adapted to their environment stunningly.  Three miles from any dry land, entire towns exist 15 ft above the water''s surface, jutting up from thousands of bamboo stilts.  Dug-out canoes taxi people from one neighborhood to another and gardens of fruits and vegetables made buoyant from lake weeds and bamboo provide abundant harvests.  Men here have perfected a one legged, one armed row which enables them to stand at the bow of the canoe, wrap their leg around the oar, and steer clear of the lake''s lush vegetation.  \n\nOur first stop was a traditional umbrella workshop.  Three teenage girls greeted our canoe at the dock and demonstrated the step-by-step process of making paper with mulberry tree fiber and carving wood pieces to construct traditional umbrellas used for shade.  They then brought us into their shop, where we were encouraged to look around and buy useless knick-knacks or hand-woven textiles.  "Buy a scarf? A necklace? Look! Woman with long neck!".  In the back corner of the floating shop, presented on a small dais in between stacked sodas and Buddha statues, was a woman of the Padaung ethnic minority - people notorious for elongating their necks with stacks of brass coils.  The sight was somewhat shocking - but not at all because of the woman''s neck - in the back corner of the store tourism and curiosity about cultural difference worked in an internecine fashion to produce a sort of human zoo.  a carnivalesque freak show.  Next to her two Padaung girls with significantly fewer brass rings sat docilely.  I felt complicit in the exploitation and commoditization of other human beings just by being there.  just by looking. And yet, I was interested.  Clearly curiosity isn''t always morally neutral...  \n\nNext we were shuttled to a silver and goldsmith shop.  A woman walked us from station to station, showing us the process of transforming ore into beautifully crafted intricate jewelry.  Another floating workshop demonstrated traditional weaving techniques using thread made from lotus plants.  \n\nWe visited a large, golden pagoda.  In the center, worshipers bowed to 5 amorphous golden blobs.  Apparently, one hundred years ago (according to local lore), these golden Mr. Potato Heads were in the likeness of Buddha.  But, thousands of sheets of gold leaf, applied dutifully by both devotees and waywards looking to store up some good karma for a rainy day, have given these Buddhas some extra curves. \n\nWe also stopped at a very strange monastery where the monks are famed to have taught cats to literally jump through hoops.  And jump they did.  Finally solves the ever present question of ''what do monks do all day?''', 'long necks, cat-filled hoops, and stilted villages', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '289-revision-2', '', '', '2012-06-19 15:06:26', '2012-06-19 15:06:26', '', 289, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=312', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
