(367, 3, '2012-06-19 15:46:59', '2012-06-19 15:46:59', 'Fried to a crisp and exhausted to the bone, like the counterparts to sailors adrift at sea, we were delighted to finally see water.  We arrived to a small town on the southern tip of Inle lake and arranged for a long boat taxi to take us around the 7 x 13 mile lake and eventually to Nyaungshwe, the main city on the northern border of Inle.  The people of Inle have adapted to their environment stunningly.  Three miles from any dry land, entire towns exist 15 ft above the water''s surface, jutting up from thousands of bamboo stilts.  Dug-out canoes taxi people from one neighborhood to another and gardens of fruits and vegetables made buoyant from lake weeds and bamboo provide abundant harvests.  Men here have perfected a one legged, one armed row which enables them to stand at the bow of the canoe, wrap their leg around the oar, and steer clear of the lake''s lush vegetation.  \r\n\r\nOur first stop was a traditional umbrella workshop.  Three teenage girls greeted our canoe at the dock and demonstrated the step-by-step process of making paper with mulberry tree fiber and carving wood pieces to construct traditional umbrellas used for shade.  They then brought us into their shop, where we were encouraged to look around and buy useless knick-knacks or hand-woven textiles.  "Buy a scarf? A necklace? Look! Woman with long neck!".  In the back corner of the floating shop, presented on a small dais in between stacked sodas and Buddha statues, was a woman of the Padaung ethnic minority - people notorious for elongating their necks with stacks of brass coils.  The sight was somewhat shocking - but not at all because of the woman''s neck - in the back corner of the store tourism and curiosity about cultural difference worked in an internecine fashion to produce a sort of human zoo.  a carnivalesque freak show.  Next to her two Padaung girls with significantly fewer brass rings sat docilely.  I felt complicit in the exploitation and commoditization of other human beings just by being there.  just by looking. And yet, I was interested.  Clearly curiosity isn''t always morally neutral...  \r\n\r\nNext we were shuttled to a silver and goldsmith shop.  A woman walked us from station to station, showing us the process of transforming ore into beautifully crafted intricate jewelry.  Another floating workshop demonstrated traditional weaving techniques using thread made from lotus plants.  Then to a local cigar making "workshop" (read: a woman''s living room) where tobacco, brown sugar and other herbs were rolled together in a banana leaf. \r\n\r\nWe visited a large, golden pagoda.  In the center, worshipers bowed to 5 amorphous golden blobs.  Apparently, one hundred years ago (according to local lore), these golden Mr. Potato Heads were in the likeness of Buddha.  But, thousands of sheets of gold leaf, applied dutifully by both devotees and waywards looking to store up some good karma for a rainy day, have given these Buddhas some extra curves. \r\n\r\nWe also stopped at a very strange monastery where the monks are famed to have taught cats to literally jump through hoops.  And jump they did.  Finally solves the ever present question of ''what do monks do all day?''\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=324"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-231130.jpg" alt="20120619-231130.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'How monks pass the time.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '289-revision-7', '', '', '2012-06-19 15:46:59', '2012-06-19 15:46:59', '', 289, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=367', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(368, 2, '2012-06-19 16:58:44', '2012-06-19 16:58:44', 'An early morning bus transported us from the dry flat plains of Bagan through winding roads that seemed to go more up than forward to the cool, misty, mountain top village of Kalaw.  Once there we made arrangements with a local guide, a native of Burma named Toto (we make no attempts at correct spelling of names here), to take us by foot the remaining 60 km to Inle Lake, the final destination for our tour of Burma.  After a full day in Kalaw of recovering from long bus rides and the sun drenched day of cycling in Bagan, we donned ponchos and started our three day trek early Thursday morning.  By mid morning the rain had cleared and we found ourselves on an uphill march through red mud beneath a canopy of trees.  Aside from frequent stops to pluck leaches from our arms and legs, the morning hike was beautiful, reminiscent of southern Appalachia''s Smokey Mountains or the Cloud Forests of Costa Rica.  By lunch time (or 2 hours after lunch time by Ali''s watch) we''d walked upward until there was no more up to go and stopped for lunch at a Nepalese family''s house which Toto aptly called "the Viewpoint".\n\nDuring the reminder of the day we walked through small villages nestled on hillsides and past the rectangular ponds created by terraced rice paddies while quickly becoming soaked by the afternoons frequent and relentless downpours.  We arrived at a small village cursing our saturated socks and mud-caked shoes just as it started getting dark and were welcomed with a hot fire, a warm meal, and blankets and pillows laid out on the floor of the unadorned, unfurnished main room of a local family''s home.  The three of us (Ali, Kasey, and I) sat on the floor and tore into enough mouth-watering food to feed 12.  We finished dinner around 8 pm, and I pulled out a deck of cards suggesting a game of Hearts.  Kasey and Ali looked at each other and in agreement proposed an alternate plan.  "I''d be ok with just going to bed."\n\nWe woke with the roosters (but somehow after Toto and our host and chef, Johay) and were met with a breakfast equal in enormity and deliciousness to the previous evening''s dinner.   Let me be frank.  Burmese food is not, in general, good.  There''s a reason you don''t find many Burmese restaurants outside of Burma. What we had in Yangon, Bagan, and Kalaw was either very fried, very oily, or often both.  But Johay''s meals shook the foundation of all I had come to know about Burmese cuisine over the previous week.  So it was with mixed emotions that we took the news that Toto would be unable to accompany us for the remainding two days to Inle due to a prior foot injury exacerbated by the previous day''s hike, and that Johay would take us the rest of the way.  While much less talkative than Toto (Johay knew only a few words of English), Johay proved an excellent guide cutting through the beautiful rolling hills of Burmese farmlands plowed by oxen and harvested by hand.  We were blessed with a day of clouds, mist, and no rain.  Late in the afternoon, gesturing with our hands and with exhausted expressions we asked Johay how much further we would walk that day.  He pointed to a pagoda on a mountain far in the distance.  It was time for a quick rest.\n\nWe reached a monastery equipped with thin sleeping mats and thick blankets an hour before sunset.  We washed as well as we could and started a game of cards while Johay disappeared.  Two hours later he miraculously reappeared with two platters full of food.  Where did this food come from?  Had Johay been carrying it in his backpack this whole time?  Our questions were answered when we headed out early the next morning and noticed that Johay''s pack had shrunk to a third of its previous day''s size.\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234615.jpg" alt="20120619-234615.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234608.jpg" alt="20120619-234608.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'beautiful, bloodsucking burma: trekking from Kalaw to Inle Lake', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '286-autosave', '', '', '2012-06-19 16:58:44', '2012-06-19 16:58:44', '', 286, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=368', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
