d."\n\nWe woke with the roosters (but somehow after Toto and our host and chef, Johay) and were met with a breakfast equal in enormity and deliciousness to the previous evening''s dinner.   Let me be frank.  Burmese food is not, in general, good.  There''s a reason you don''t find many Burmese restaurants outside of Burma. What we had in Yangon, Bagan, and Kalaw was either very fried, very oily, or often both.  But Johay''s meals shook the foundation of all I had come to know about Burmese cuisine over the previous week.  So it was with mixed emotions that we took the news that Toto would be unable to accompany us for the remainding two days to Inle due to a prior foot injury exacerbated by the previous day''s hike, and that Johay would take us the rest of the way.  While much less talkative than Toto (Johay knew only a few words of English), Johay proved an excellent guide cutting through the beautiful rolling hills of Burmese farmlands plowed by oxen and harvested by hand.  We were blessed with a day of clouds, mist, and no rain.  Late in the afternoon, gesturing with our hands and with exhausted expressions we asked Johay how much further we would walk that day.  He pointed to a pagoda on a mountain far in the distance.  It was time for a quick rest.\n\nWe reached a monastery equipped with thin sleeping mats and thick blankets an hour before sunset.  We washed as well as we could and started a game of cards while Johay disappeared.  Two hours later he miraculously reappeared with two platters full of food.  Where did this food come from?  Had Johay been carrying it in his backpack this whole time?  Our questions were answered when we headed out early the next morning and noticed that Johay''s pack had shrunk to a third of its previous day''s size.\n\n\n\n\n<blockquote></blockquote>', 'beautiful, bloodsucking burma: trekking from Kalaw to Inle Lake', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '286-revision-10', '', '', '2012-06-19 16:36:48', '2012-06-19 16:36:48', '', 286, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=369', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(370, 3, '2012-06-01 00:42:12', '2012-06-01 00:42:12', '<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120531-193913.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120531-193913.jpg" alt="20120531-193913.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'adam & ali', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2-revision-3', '', '', '2012-06-01 00:42:12', '2012-06-01 00:42:12', '', 2, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=370', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(371, 3, '2012-06-21 15:47:38', '2012-06-21 15:47:38', '<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120531-193913.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120531-193913.jpg" alt="20120531-193913.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\nali:  Traveling is my passion. I love the opportunity for discovery that it provides. I joke that most of the decisions I make in life are guided by the single desire to have good stories to tell over dinner. I am only half joking. After losing all I owned, I once hitchhiked from Costa Rica to Arizona. I''ve slept in the same room as a green mamba - which, upon discovery, I ate. After participating in a local ceremony for warriors in West Africa, the traditional healer assures me that I am bullet-proof. I also like warm milk with cinnamon before bed, laughing until I cry, dancing without inhibition (and better yet, in costume!), and picking scabs until they bleed.\n\n\nadam:  i love music.  listening and making. especially with others.  i ride my bike a lot.  once i rode from london to budapest.  people were friendly and cars didn''t run over me.  i camped in parks and slept on stranger''s floors.  i came back with the knowledge of how much i''d taken ranch dressing and obesity for granted. i have a phd in physics and i am a huge fan of wikipedia and npr.', 'about us.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2-revision-4', '', '', '2012-06-21 15:47:38', '2012-06-21 15:47:38', '', 2, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=371', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(372, 3, '2012-06-04 18:20:49', '2012-06-04 18:20:49', 'five airports, four cities, three flights, and one day later, adam and i find ourselves in london.  \r\n\r\nyesterday, we spent (a far insufficient) three hours roaming the streets (and subways) of NYC.  We ate dollar pizza, met up with a friend at a beautiful hotel, and absorbed the frenetic energy of downtown.  new york is big, loud, busy, dirty, and yet against all odds, surprisingly friendly - fittingly iconic of america(ns).  i am so looking forward to our return there in august.\r\n\r\nSandwiched between two overnight flights, we visited one of my dearest friends, Leslie, in London. The city was buzzing with excitement over the queen''s jubilee weekend. In honor or such a lofty occasion, les greeted us with a traditional English tea.  It turns out that "clotted cream" isn''t nearly as disgusting as the name would lead one to believe.  We spent the day exploring east London, relishing in the rare moments of sunlight, and,naturally, eating. \r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=102"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120603-073919.jpg" alt="20120603-073919.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=102"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120603-073845.jpg" alt="20120603-073845.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=102"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120603-073826.jpg" alt="20120603-073826.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=102"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120603-073854.jpg" alt="20120603-073854.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=102"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120603-100100.jpg" alt="20120603-100100.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=102"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120603-100114.jpg" alt="20120603-100114.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'five airports, four cities, three flights, and one day later', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision-11', '', '', '2012-06-04 18:20:49', '2012-06-04 18:20:49', '', 79, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=372', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(373, 3, '2012-06-06 09:30:45', '2012-06-06 09:30:45', 'A sleepless night of packing, followed by two consecutive nights of dozing  in airports and planes, we arrived in Mumbai exhausted in the early evening of our third full day of traveling.  We splurged and spent an extra $2 on a taxi with AC.  Worth every rupee.  The hour long ride to our hotel  was both dreadful and amazing.  Five lanes of cars, motorbikes, and autorickshaws, all pushing their way down a three lane road, making their presence known with a near constant buzz of their horns.  With automobiles so tightly packed, I could have, at any time, reached over and honked the horn of the car next to us.  Please keep your arms in the vehicle at all times.  If you want to keep them that is.  After depositing our packs at the Royal Castle Hotel, we went out to take in the city.  Mumbai is fantastic.  Vibrant, dirty, teaming with people, and nearly apathetic of our existence.\n\nToday we awoke early (unable to sleep due to jet lag) and did a bit more roaming, looking for something delicious for breakfast and a strong cup of coffee.  Afterwards we packed up our belongings and grabbed a taxi to the India Guest House in Colaba.  The 20 minute, un-air conditioned ride made me glad we''d opted for AC on the previous day.  After checking in, we again hit the city, wandering past the famous Taj Mahal Hotel and into the Gateway of India where we arranged for a taxi to drive us to all of the obligatory tourist stops: Dhobi Ghaat, open air laundry; Worli Fishing Village; Mani Bhavan Gandhi Museum; etc...  We came back to the hotel early and took a long, much need nap, before heading out for our first true Indian dining experience.  Paneer Tikka Masala for me and Vegetable Korma for Ali.  Absolutely delicious.\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231052.jpg" alt="20120604-231052.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231101.jpg" alt="20120604-231101.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231109.jpg" alt="20120604-231109.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231115.jpg" alt="20120604-231115.jpg" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162322.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162322.jpg" alt="20120606-162322.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162331.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162331.jpg" alt="20120606-162331.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'india is great.  horn ok please.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '176-revision-8', '', '', '2012-06-06 09:30:45', '2012-06-06 09:30:45', '', 176, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=373', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(374, 3, '2012-06-19 16:53:34', '2012-06-19 16:53:34', 'An early morning bus transported us from the dry flat plains of Bagan through winding roads that seemed to go more up than forward to the cool, misty, mountain top village of Kalaw.  Once there we made arrangements with a local guide, a native of Burma named Toto (we make no attempts at correct spelling of names here), to take us by foot the rest of the way to Inle Lake, our final destination for our tour of Burma.  After a full day in Kalaw of recovering from long bus rides and the sun drenched day of cycling in Bagan, we donned ponchos and started our three day trek early Thursday morning.  By mid morning the rain had cleared and we found ourselves on an uphill march through red mud beneath a canopy of trees.  Aside from frequent stops to pluck leaches from our arms and legs, the morning hike was beautiful, reminiscent of southern Appalachia''s Smokey Mountains or the Cloud Forests of Costa Rica.  By lunch time (or 2 hours after lunch time by Ali''s watch) we''d walked upward until there was no more up to go and stopped for lunch at a Nepalese family''s house which Toto aptly called "the Viewpoint".\r\n\r\nDuring the reminder of the day we walked through small villages nestled on hillsides and past the rectangular ponds created by terraced rice paddies while quickly becoming soaked by the afternoons frequent and relentless downpours.  We arrived at a small village cursing our saturated socks and mud-caked shoes just as it started getting dark and were welcomed with a hot fire, a warm meal, and blankets and pillows laid out on the floor of the unadorned, unfurnished main room of a local family''s home.  The three of us (Ali, Kasey, and I) sat on the floor and tore into enough mouth-watering food to feed 12.  We finished dinner around 8 pm, and I pulled out a deck of cards suggesting a game of Hearts.  Kasey and Ali looked at each other and in agreement proposed an alternate plan.  "I''d be ok with just going to bed."\r\n\r\nWe woke with the roosters (but somehow after Toto and our host and chef, Johay) and were met with a breakfast equal in enormity and deliciousness to the previous evening''s dinner.   Let me be frank.  Burmese food is not, in general, good.  There''s a reason you don''t find many Burmese restaurants outside of Burma. What we had in Yangon, Bagan, and Kalaw was either very fried, very oily, or often both.  But Johay''s meals shook the foundation of all I had come to know about Burmese cuisine over the previous week.  So it was with mixed emotions that we took the news that Toto would be unable to accompany us for the remainding two days to Inle due to a prior foot injury exacerbated by the previous day''s hike, and that Johay would take us the rest of the way.  While much less talkative than Toto (Johay knew only a few words of English), Johay proved an excellent guide cutting through the beautiful rolling hills of Burmese farmlands plowed by oxen and harvested by hand.  We were blessed with a day of clouds, mist, and no rain.  Late in the afternoon, gesturing with our hands and with exhausted expressions we asked Johay how much further we would walk that day.  He pointed to a pagoda on a mountain far in the distance.  It was time for a quick rest.\r\n\r\nWe reached a monastery equipped with thin sleeping mats and thick blankets an hour before sunset.  We washed as well as we could and started a game of cards while Johay disappeared.  Two hours later he miraculously reappeared with two platters full of food.  Where did this food come from?  Had Johay been carrying it in his backpack this whole time?  Our questions were answered when we headed out early the next morning and noticed that Johay''s pack had shrunk to a third of its previous day''s size.\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234615.jpg" alt="20120619-234615.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234608.jpg" alt="20120619-234608.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'beautiful, bloodsucking burma: trekking from Kalaw to Inle Lake', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '286-revision-11', '', '', '2012-06-19 16:53:34', '2012-06-19 16:53:34', '', 286, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=374', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
