(411, 3, '2012-06-13 07:01:22', '2012-06-13 07:01:22', 'After our 4th overnight flight in 6 days, we arrived in Bangkok to meet up with Adam''s friend, Kasey.  From the airport we sped past imposing skyscrapers and sprawling apartment complexes (occasionally dotted with an imposing Buddha statue or temple).  There was no filth, chaos, or disarray to be seen.  Manicured and high tech, Bangkok presents itself to the world. \r\n\r\nAnd so we arrived in the backpacker''s ghetto, Khao San. Every business in this area is catered to tourists: massage parlors, restaurants, bars, clubs, hotels, internet cafes, shopping centers, coffee shops.  Everything is open.  You are invited (nay, commanded) in everywhere.  Bright multi-colored lights twinkle,  loud reggae or lady gaga blares from every speaker,  every ten feet a big neon sign announces drink specials, tours, or sex shows. loose fitting tank tops and tight t-shirts with drawings of bicycles and vintage cameras, screen prints of kubrick''s "full metal jacket", or of a naked woman snorting coke which forms the letters of "facebook", even banksey prints, spill over into the road.  Ironic and aloof - straight from an urban outfitter''s catalogue.  meanwhile, hordes of young, attractive, scantily clad westerners roam aimlessly drinking and eating, buying, smoking, nursing hang-overs, and hitting on one another.  \r\n\r\nFrom this angle, it appears that bangkok not only thrives on tourism - tourists are bangkok .  Indeed, Thais do not appear to be consuming Bangkok at all - their only role here is of purveyors of food, booze, massages, whatever you need... Strange to visit a place where the people remain invisible. \r\n\r\nTourists gather together in bars and cafes, swapping stories of how they''ve been scammed, rolling their eyes, sighing -- "ugh. thailand!".  An open hostility between tourists and thais is palpable.  A sign in our hostel says "We do not allow Thai people to go upstairs.  No matter the reason".  Not only are the tourists convinced that Thais are scammers, hustlers, and thieves, apparently so is the Thai management (or at least they are complicit in perpetuating this image).  There is something repulsive about the tourist who comes to visit a country only to fear and desire containment from it''s population.  \r\n\r\nOne problem with a place like this is that when we are surrounded by people who are just like us, we forget that maybe the rules ought to change a bit, we forget that we are playing on someone else''s field.  And so, the question remains, what is the point of traveling? Why do we spend thousands of dollars to fly across oceans when we only want to replicate home? an inherent ambivalence of the human spirit, the desire to see, feel, touch and taste what lies beyond, and yet the (understandable) desire to stay where we are comfortable?\r\n\r\nBut, walk a mile from this place, and the white faces, short shorts, and enormous backpacks begin to disappear, replaced by a bustling city, grocery stores, and old women who bow to greet one another .  Alas! There is a real city beyond the neon glare!  \r\n\r\nYesterday we explored the residential streets, local markets, and public spaces of Thai bangkok.  We stumbled across hundreds of tents in front of the parliament building.  In celebration of the day of Vesak, Buddha''s 2,600th year from attaining enlightenment, a group had gathered to cook and share free food for everyone.  Rather than being met as outsiders, the people invited us to join, took us from stall to stall, encouraging us to share a meal.  Old women tugged me from one place to another, filling my arms with rambutan (a red fruit native to here covered in spikes and filled with a lychee-like jelly), popcorn, noodles, and bananas.  There was a large stage where people spoke, danced, and sung.  Big bags of rice and other food staples were being handed out for free to those in need.    \r\n\r\nAnd so, with our faiths somewhat restored, we headed back to the neon, and yes, ended the night with a $3 foot massage.  \r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=216"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120608-093711.jpg" alt="20120608-093711.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'bangkok: the cancun of southeast asia', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '221-revision-3', '', '', '2012-06-13 07:01:22', '2012-06-13 07:01:22', '', 221, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=411', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(412, 3, '2012-06-26 07:37:09', '2012-06-26 07:37:09', '', '20120626-153659.jpg', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '20120626-153659-jpg', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:37:09', '2012-06-26 07:37:09', '', 228, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153659.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(413, 3, '2012-06-13 06:58:30', '2012-06-13 06:58:30', 'We arrived early Saturday morning, unprepared for what was in store.  The airport was tiny, reflecting the 17 year-long tourism boycott which ended only two years ago.  At the airport we were met by men wearing longyi --long traditional skirts, and women whose entire faces were painted yellow.  Initially I thought it was for the benefit of tourists, a kitschy show of traditional culture. Turns out, unlike most countries where men wear western clothing while women are the carriers of culture, in Myanmar it is the men who wear traditional clothing while women dress in imported Chinese blouses and skirts.  The women, however, don''t pass as entirely western.  Women and children paint large circles, intricate lines, or entire masks of  tha nap khar, a yellowish paste made from wood, on their faces.  \r\n\r\nWe soon discovered that Myanmar does not accept cards.  No one.  No where. None whatsoever.  One must exchange precious US dollars.  And not just any dollars. Myanmar does not accept bills more than six years old, torn, worn, folded, or otherwise show any sign of use.  Myanmar apparently also has a delusional conception of their currency''s worth.  At the airport, government registered money changers offer an exchange rate of $1 USD for 8 Kyat, while just outside the airport doors the "black-market" offers 840 Kyat for $1 USD.   So, we scrounged together whatever we had, using heavy books and moist towels in a true mafioso fashion to turn our crumpled, old dollars into something acceptable to the street-corner, back-door money changers.   Alas.  We largely failed.  \r\n\r\nIn our two days in Yangon, we could count all the westerners we saw on our fingers.  Due to the bad international press, heavy travel restrictions, and difficulty obtaining a visa, only the most intrepid travelers, or those anxious to escape the heavily trodden backpacker circuit of southeast asia, make their way to Myanmar.  Billboards dot the country which read "Myanmar welcomes and takes care of tourists".  This is a message that the people have truly taken to heart.    There is little to no haggling on price.  We never felt taken advantage of, preyed upon, extorted or otherwise abused here. While I risk making absurd generalizations that no population could live up to, our impression was  that Burmese people are open, honest, generous with their time, and curious about us.  Every person we passed greeted us with a wave and a large smile, little kids ran up to dole out high fives, and mothers encouraged their toddlers to blow kisses at us.  Really a refreshing change of pace for the calloused traveler, always on guard, always cynical.  \r\n\r\nWe could also count all of the overt signs of a military presence: Zero. For a country known internationally for a military that abuses, rapes, murders, silences, and systematically strips away rights from its people, the strong arm of the state was illusive. Most shops openly posted photographs of Aung San Suu Kyi, who, likened to Nelson Mandela and having received the Nobel Peace Prize,  is a national hero and represents hope for political reform.  We even witnessed a protest.  At Shwedagon Paya, a large (and astoundingly beautiful) temple complex in the center of the city, Buddhist monks (who have historically been loud and visible in their dissent against the government) and lay people from Rakhin state condemned the government for not protecting its people from politically and religiously motivated acts of violence (allegedly) committed by Bangladeshis on the two nations'' border.   \r\n\r\nAlong with being on the front line for political reform, monks, clad in flowing red robes, continued to shatter our preconceptions of serene, docile, and otherworldly beings.  In Myanmar,which is described as the most devout Buddhist country in the world, all boys and men are expected to shave their heads, don robes, and pick up alms bowls at least twice in their lives, once in boyhood, and once after becoming a man.  As a result, the line between monks and lay people is fuzzy.  Many monks smoke cigarettes, are covered in tattoos, and spend their days watching soccer and eating snacks with their buddies.  It took us a long time to become accustomed to the sight of a monk reclining at a street-side cafe, eating peanuts and giggling with friends.    Yes, perhaps I could be a monk when I grow up...\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=234"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-124624.jpg" alt="20120613-124624.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Hello Burma! Or should I call you Myanmar?...', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '228-revision-4', '', '', '2012-06-13 06:58:30', '2012-06-13 06:58:30', '', 228, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=413', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(414, 3, '2012-06-26 07:40:42', '2012-06-26 07:40:42', '', '20120626-154035.jpg', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '20120626-154035-jpg', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:40:42', '2012-06-26 07:40:42', '', 230, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154035.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(415, 3, '2012-06-19 14:57:39', '2012-06-19 14:57:39', 'Sunday evening we hopped on an overnight bus north to Bagan, a region in central Myanmar speckled with over 4000 ancient Buddhist temples.  In the morning we rented cheap single speed cruisers and headed toward the largest and most impressive of these structures.  While most of the temples we passed were just large enough to house a single 15 foot tall sitting Buddha statue and a handful of admirers, others towered nearly 200 feet above Bagan''s low-lying shrubbery.  The temples, all built between 1057 and 1287 A.D., still appeared to be active places of worship for the people ofBagan.  In front of many of the stupas, women sold wreaths of orange blossoms and other flowers which local people placed as offerings in front of the serene Buddhas.  The temples themselves were plain and worn, ungracefully showing their age.  The Buddha statues housed in most were nearly identical: legs crossed with a mysterious half-smile.  We spent most of the day hopping from temple to temple, ducking inside just long enough to escape the oppressive mid-day sun and discover that, yes, this buddha does indeed look just like the last.  While the temples'' interiors were mostly unremarkable, contrasted against the sun scorched terrain, their silhouettes seemed almost alien.  It wasn''t until we climbed to the top of one of the taller pagodas and looked far across the landscape below that I finally felt a sense of awe.  Holy cow.  There really are thousands of these things.\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-130351.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-130351.jpg" alt="20120613-130351.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', '24 hours in Bagan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '230-revision-6', '', '', '2012-06-19 14:57:39', '2012-06-19 14:57:39', '', 230, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=415', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(416, 3, '2012-06-26 07:42:00', '2012-06-26 07:42:00', '', '20120626-154150.jpg', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '20120626-154150-jpg', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:42:00', '2012-06-26 07:42:00', '', 286, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154150.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(417, 3, '2012-06-22 11:53:19', '2012-06-22 11:53:19', 'An early morning bus transported us from the dry flat plains of Bagan through winding roads that seemed to go more up than forward to the cool, misty, mountain top village of Kalaw.  Once there we made arrangements with a local guide, a native of Burma named Toto (we make no attempts at correct spelling of names here), to take us by foot the rest of the way to Inle Lake, our final destination for our tour of Burma.  After a full day in Kalaw of recovering from long bus rides and the sun drenched day of cycling in Bagan, we donned ponchos and started our three day trek early Thursday morning.  By mid morning the rain had cleared and we found ourselves on an uphill march through red mud beneath a canopy of trees.  Aside from frequent stops to pluck leaches from our arms and legs, the morning hike was beautiful, reminiscent of southern Appalachia''s Smokey Mountains or the Cloud Forests of Costa Rica.  By lunch time (or 2 hours after lunch time by Ali''s watch) we''d walked upward until there was no more up to go and stopped for lunch at a Nepalese family''s house which Toto aptly called "the Viewpoint".\r\n\r\nDuring the reminder of the day we walked through small villages nestled on hillsides and past the rectangular ponds created by terraced rice paddies while quickly becoming soaked by the afternoons frequent and relentless downpours.  We arrived at a small village cursing our saturated socks and mud-caked shoes just as it started getting dark and were welcomed with a hot fire, a warm meal, and blankets and pillows laid out on the floor of the unadorned, unfurnished main room of a local family''s home.  The three of us (Ali, Kasey, and I) sat on the floor and tore into enough mouth-watering food to feed 12.  We finished dinner around 8 pm, and I pulled out a deck of cards suggesting a game of Hearts.  Kasey and Ali looked at each other and in agreement proposed an alternate plan.  "I''d be ok with just going to bed."\r\n\r\nWe woke with the roosters (but somehow after Toto and our host and chef, Johay) and were met with a breakfast equal in enormity and deliciousness to the previous evening''s dinner.   Let me be frank.  Burmese food is not, in general, good.  There''s a reason you don''t find many Burmese restaurants outside of Burma. What we had in Yangon, Bagan, and Kalaw was either very fried, very oily, or often both.  But Johay''s meals shook the foundation of all I had come to know about Burmese cuisine over the previous week.  So it was with mixed emotions that we took the news that Toto would be unable to accompany us for the remainding two days to Inle due to a prior foot injury exacerbated by the previous day''s hike, and that Johay would take us the rest of the way.  While much less talkative than Toto (Johay knew only a few words of English), Johay proved an excellent guide cutting through the beautiful rolling hills of Burmese farmlands plowed by oxen and harvested by hand.  We were blessed with a day of clouds, mist, and no rain.  Late in the afternoon, gesturing with our hands and with exhausted expressions we asked Johay how much further we would walk that day.  He pointed to a pagoda on a mountain far in the distance.  It was time for a quick rest.\r\n\r\nWe reached a monastery equipped with thin sleeping mats and thick blankets an hour before sunset.  We washed as well as we could and started a game of cards while Johay disappeared.  Two hours later he miraculously reappeared with two platters full of food.  Where did this food come from?  Had Johay been carrying it in his backpack this whole time?  Our questions were answered when we headed out early the next morning and noticed that Johay''s pack had shrunk to a third of its previous day''s size.\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234615.jpg" alt="20120619-234615.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=309"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120619-234608.jpg" alt="20120619-234608.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'beautiful, bloodsucking burma: trekking from Kalaw to Inle Lake', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '286-revision-12', '', '', '2012-06-22 11:53:19', '2012-06-22 11:53:19', '', 286, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=417', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(418, 3, '2012-06-26 07:42:43', '2012-06-26 07:42:43', '', '20120626-154239.jpg', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '20120626-154239-jpg', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:42:43', '2012-06-26 07:42:43', '', 390, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154239.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(419, 3, '2012-06-25 00:42:42', '2012-06-25 00:42:42', 'Insufficient travel research sometimes takes you to unexpected places.  And with some luck, that''s not a bad thing.  Our original plan was to take a bus from Inle Lake to Tachileik, a town in Burma which Lonely Planet and wikitravel.org both list as a Thailand/Burma "border crossing".  From Tachileik we planned to cross into  Mae Sai and continue on the short distance to Laos, the next country on our itinary.  But "border crossing" in this case is a bit of a misleading term.  If we had read a little more, we would have learned that the Tachileik/Mae Sai border crossing only exists to allow for day trips from Mae Sai to Tachileik (but no further than the few souvenir stands catering to tourists who want to cross Myanmar off their "I''ve been there" list).  Going from Burma to Thailand requires a permit from the Burmese government which must be applied for at least two weeks in advance (i.e. well before we even knew we were going to Burma).  And even if we wanted to try our luck with an illicit crossing, it''s impossible to even get to Tachileik from any other part of Burma by road.  No busses, taxis, or rickshaws can take you there.  Our only option: a 14 hour bus ride in the opposite direction of Laos to take a flight out of Yangon''s tiny international airport.\n\nDisheartened by the prospect of flying further away from Laos back to Bangkok and losing 2-3 days on more cross country bus rides, we investigated alternative options.  Yangon''s airport is small, but it does offer flights to a few places other than Bangkok.  Maybe Beijing?  Could be interesting, but we don''t have a visa.  Kolkata?  Probably later, but we''re not done with southeast Asia.  Kuala Lumpur?  Hmm...\n\nAnd so, we purchased two tickets to Malaysia, knowing only that 1) it wasn''t Bangkok, and 2) tickets to there from Burma were pretty cheap.  A quick skim of Frommers informed us that Borneo (an island shared by Malaysia, Indonesia, and Brunei) is the place to go for excellent scuba diving and pristine jungles.  We arrived at Kuala Lumpur late Monday night, were on a plane to Borneo''s largest airport in Kota Kinabalu early Tuesday morning, and spent the rest of the day scrambling to make arrangements for the next 7 days.  Borneo, slightly larger than the state of Texas, can be overwhelming without adequate planning.  Add to that the fact that Sabah (Malaysia''s northern state in Borneo) is a tourist Mecca for China and Indonesia, we were lucky to squeeze in arrangements for a 4 day scuba diving course followed immediately by 3 days of boat rides and trekking through the jungles of Kinabatangan minutes before Kota Kinabalu''s booking offices closed.\n\nAt 7 the next morning we took a 2 hour van ride, followed by a 45 minute boat ride to Mantanani Island, where we would spend the next 4 days scuba diving and snorkeling.  While Borneo is an island like Greenland is an island, Mantanani is more akin to Gilligan''s Island.  Populated by two small villages of fishermen, the backpackers lodge we stayed at consisted of a dozen simple treehouse style bungalows just large enough for a few twin size mattresses and was the only short term sleeping accomodation on the island.\n\nI''ll be the first to admit that vacationing at the beach is highly overrated.  It''s hot, sand gets in everything, salt water feels like acid in your eyes, and the up and down and up and down of the waves is nauseating.  There is so much to hate about the beach.  And yet a snorkel and a pair of goggles can make it all worthwhile.  Exploring a coral reef is like visiting another planet.  Brilliant colors and marine life ranging from beautiful to bizarre.\n\nBorneo is world renowned for its scuba diving sites, but most master divers skip over Mantanani, heading straight for Borneo''s more flashy dive sites.  However, this neglect by the more experienced divers seems to make Mantanani an ideal spot for a beginner to master the basics of scuba diving, while enjoying the crystal clear waters of the South China Sea and all the marine life one can take in in 45 minute increments.\n\nBecoming scuba certified (which allows for unassisted, independent scuba diving around the world) in the states can be prohibitively expensive due the cost of instructors, gear rental, and trips to divable bodies of water.  Also, they can be a bit boring as much of the preliminary training on buoyancy control, breathing exercises, operating your gear, and avoiding the bends takes place in a classroom or confined water (which in the states, usually means a swimming pool).  However, when scuba certification courses are taken in a place like, let''s say, Borneo, the bookwork takes place on beachside table, and the "confined water" dives 30 meters off the coast of a remote island teeming with marine life.  During our 4 open water dives (far from the coast and 18 meters down) we saw sting rays, eels, crabs, scorpion fish, lion fish, star fish, clown fish, puffer fish, and many (many) other fish whose names we never learned.  Floating weightlessly just above expanses of coral reefs was surreal. And the experience of breathing underwater was ... well... breathtaking.  \n\n<br><br><br>\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=384">Click here to see more photos from Mantanani</a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=384"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120623-213311.jpg" alt="20120623-213311.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'avoiding the bends in borneo', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '390-revision-11', '', '', '2012-06-25 00:42:42', '2012-06-25 00:42:42', '', 390, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=419', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
