(425, 3, '2012-06-26 07:46:56', '2012-06-26 07:46:56', 'Insufficient travel research sometimes takes you to unexpected places.  And with some luck, that''s not a bad thing.  Our original plan was to take a bus from Inle Lake to Tachileik, a town in Burma which Lonely Planet and wikitravel.org both list as a Thailand/Burma "border crossing".  From Tachileik we planned to cross into  Mae Sai and continue on the short distance to Laos, the next country on our itinary.  But "border crossing" in this case is a bit of a misleading term.  If we had read a little more, we would have learned that the Tachileik/Mae Sai border crossing only exists to allow for day trips from Mae Sai to Tachileik (but no further than the few souvenir stands catering to tourists who want to cross Myanmar off their "I''ve been there" list).  Going from Burma to Thailand requires a permit from the Burmese government which must be applied for at least two weeks in advance (i.e. well before we even knew we were going to Burma).  And even if we wanted to try our luck with an illicit crossing, it''s impossible to even get to Tachileik from any other part of Burma by road.  No busses, taxis, or rickshaws can take you there.  Our only option: a 14 hour bus ride in the opposite direction of Laos to take a flight out of Yangon''s tiny international airport.\n\nDisheartened by the prospect of flying further away from Laos back to Bangkok and losing 2-3 days on more cross country bus rides, we investigated alternative options.  Yangon''s airport is small, but it does offer flights to a few places other than Bangkok.  Maybe Beijing?  Could be interesting, but we don''t have a visa.  Kolkata?  Probably later, but we''re not done with southeast Asia.  Kuala Lumpur?  Hmm...\n\nAnd so, we purchased two tickets to Malaysia, knowing only that 1) it wasn''t Bangkok, and 2) tickets to there from Burma were pretty cheap.  A quick skim of Frommers informed us that Borneo (an island shared by Malaysia, Indonesia, and Brunei) is the place to go for excellent scuba diving and pristine jungles.  We arrived at Kuala Lumpur late Monday night, were on a plane to Borneo''s largest airport in Kota Kinabalu early Tuesday morning, and spent the rest of the day scrambling to make arrangements for the next 7 days.  Borneo, slightly larger than the state of Texas, can be overwhelming without adequate planning.  Add to that the fact that Sabah (Malaysia''s northern state in Borneo) is a tourist Mecca for China and Indonesia, we were lucky to squeeze in arrangements for a 4 day scuba diving course followed immediately by 3 days of boat rides and trekking through the jungles of Kinabatangan minutes before Kota Kinabalu''s booking offices closed.\n\nAt 7 the next morning we took a 2 hour van ride, followed by a 45 minute boat ride to Mantanani Island, where we would spend the next 4 days scuba diving and snorkeling.  While Borneo is an island like Greenland is an island, Mantanani is more akin to Gilligan''s Island.  Populated by two small villages of fishermen, the backpackers lodge we stayed at consisted of a dozen simple treehouse style bungalows just large enough for a few twin size mattresses and was the only short term sleeping accomodation on the island.\n\nI''ll be the first to admit that vacationing at the beach is highly overrated.  It''s hot, sand gets in everything, salt water feels like acid in your eyes, and the up and down and up and down of the waves is nauseating.  There is so much to hate about the beach.  And yet a snorkel and a pair of goggles can make it all worthwhile.  Exploring a coral reef is like visiting another planet.  Brilliant colors and marine life ranging from beautiful to bizarre.\n\nBorneo is world renowned for its scuba diving sites, but most master divers skip over Mantanani, heading straight for Borneo''s more flashy dive sites.  However, this neglect by the more experienced divers seems to make Mantanani an ideal spot for a beginner to master the basics of scuba diving, while enjoying the crystal clear waters of the South China Sea and all the marine life one can take in in 45 minute increments.\n\nBecoming scuba certified (which allows for unassisted, independent scuba diving around the world) in the states can be prohibitively expensive due the cost of instructors, gear rental, and trips to divable bodies of water.  Also, they can be a bit boring as much of the preliminary training on buoyancy control, breathing exercises, operating your gear, and avoiding the bends takes place in a classroom or confined water (which in the states, usually means a swimming pool).  However, when scuba certification courses are taken in a place like, let''s say, Borneo, the bookwork takes place on beachside table, and the "confined water" dives 30 meters off the coast of a remote island teeming with marine life.  During our 4 open water dives (far from the coast and 18 meters down) we saw sting rays, eels, crabs, scorpion fish, lion fish, star fish, clown fish, puffer fish, and many (many) other fish whose names we never learned.  Floating weightlessly just above expanses of coral reefs was surreal. And the experience of breathing underwater was ... well... breathtaking.  \n\n<br><br><br>\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=384">Click here to see more photos from Mantanani</a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154454.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-154454.jpg" alt="20120626-154454.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120623-142211.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120623-142211.jpg" alt="20120623-142211.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'avoiding the bends in borneo', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '390-revision-14', '', '', '2012-06-26 07:46:56', '2012-06-26 07:46:56', '', 390, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=425', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
