ilently hoped to see the elusive, endangered orangutan (which in Malay means "man of the forest").  And -- remarkably-- we did.  Two black masses silhouetted in the heights of a fig tree slowly began to move.  And move closer.  Soon, we could make out a mom and her child, leisurely spanning out their seemingly indeterminable limbs to grab figs and pop them one by one into their mouths.  The sun began to set, and we watched as the orangutans climbed out of the fig tree and into the tree directly in front of us in order to construct a nest where they''d pass the night.  Branch by branch, the nest was made.  And soon they tucked themselves in for the night.  And so, contented and covered in scabs from leeches and patches of mud, we did the same.<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111552.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111552.jpg" alt="20120627-111552.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111605.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111605.jpg" alt="20120627-111605.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'sometimes you eat the fish.  sometimes the fish eat you.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '429-revision-13', '', '', '2012-06-27 04:24:11', '2012-06-27 04:24:11', '', 429, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=466', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
