heir 20s from New Zealand.\n\nAs we left the crowded fishing port, we began to pass small islands of limestone rock, partially covered by green vegetation, jutting more than 100 m straight out of the water.  The bay is densely populated with these limeston monuments, some like tall buildings, others like fortress walls.\n\nAfter a few hours of cruising through the bay and snapping picture after picture that we knew couldn''t do it justice, we stopped at one of the larger islands, climbed a few dozen stairs half way to the top and found a cave illuminated by generator powered lights.  50 m in, the cave opened again to the outside revealing a gigantic pool of still green water completely surrounded by a ring of towering limestone.\n\nThe rest of the two days wast spent eating delicious freshly caught sea food, napping and reading on the top deck, escaping the heat with plunges into the ocean, and exploring more caves and secluded pools and beaches by kayak.  In the evening after our first day on the water, the air had cooled and the sky was clear.  We pulled down the sheet which had provided shade in the heat of the day and dragged a couple of mattresses from the sleeping quarters to the top deck, laid on our backs and fell asleep looking for shooting stars.<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235342.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235342.jpg" alt="20120701-235342.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235350.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235350.jpg" alt="20120701-235350.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Ha Long: where the dragon descends into the sea', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '490-revision-6', '', '', '2012-07-01 16:57:42', '2012-07-01 16:57:42', '', 490, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=502', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
