heir 20s from New Zealand.\n\nAs we left the crowded fishing port, we began to pass small islands of limestone rock, partially covered by green vegetation, jutting more than 100 m straight out of the water.  The bay is densely populated with these limeston monuments, some like tall buildings, others like fortress walls.\n\nAfter a few hours of cruising through the bay and snapping picture after picture that we knew couldn''t do it justice, we stopped at one of the larger islands, climbed a few dozen stairs half way to the top and found a cave illuminated by generator powered lights.  50 m in, the cave opened again to the outside revealing a gigantic pool of still green water completely surrounded by a ring of towering limestone.\n\nThe rest of the two days wast spent eating delicious freshly caught sea food, napping and reading on the top deck, escaping the heat with plunges into the ocean, and exploring more caves and secluded pools and beaches by kayak.  In the evening after our first day on the water, the air had cooled and the sky was clear.  We pulled down the sheet which had provided shade in the heat of the day and dragged a couple of mattresses from the sleeping quarters to the top deck, laid on our backs and fell asleep looking for shooting stars.\n\n<br /><br />\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=487">click to see more photos</a>\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=487"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235342.jpg" alt="20120701-235342.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235350.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235350.jpg" alt="20120701-235350.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Ha Long: where the dragon descends into the sea', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '490-revision-12', '', '', '2012-07-01 17:45:16', '2012-07-01 17:45:16', '', 490, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=515', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(516, 2, '2012-07-02 16:55:08', '2012-07-02 16:55:08', 'Traveling is a tiring endeavor. At the end of most days what we want most is a soft place to lay our heads and a good night''s sleep. Frequently we settle for just a night''s sleep (good or otherwise). On occasion we are handed a couple of hours of dozing in 15 minute increments sitting upright on a 12 hour, bumpy, loud, overnight bus ride to our next destination. A good night of sleep is occasionally forfeited by budget travelers in order to save a few bucks or to gain an extra day of sightseeing by taking overnight transportation. Sometimes it''s just the price one pays for a good adventure. Our trip thus far has been no exception. We''ve slept on airplanes, in buses, on benches in airports, in tents on the beach, and even on the deck of a boat. There has been no shortage of variety in our sleeping accommodations throughout our trip. So it was fitting that we ended up on one of Southeast Asia''s most notorious bus rides on the evening of the last day in June. A 28 hour journey crossing the Vietnam/Laos border and winding through the jungle clad mountains of northern Laos. In honor of our one month anniversary of traveling, I''ve put together the following illustrations.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[easychart type="pie" title="where we slept in june" groupnames="Hotels/Hostels,Tent,Airport,Bus,Airplane,Homestay/Monestary,Boat" group1values="16" group2values="3" group3values="3" group4values="3" group5values="2" group6values="2" group7values="1" chartfadecolor="FFFFFF"]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[easychart type="horizbarstack" height="50" width="200" title="nights slept on a mattress" groupnames="Hotels/Hostels,Tent,Airport,Bus,Airplane,Homestay/Monestary,Boat" valuenames="no mattress,mattress" group1values="0,16" group2values="3,0" group3values="3,0" group4values="3,0" group5values="2,0" group6values="2,0" group7values="0,1"]', 'A place to rest our heads', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-place-to-rest-our-heads', '', '', '2013-01-28 06:19:15', '2013-01-28 06:19:15', '', 0, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=516', 0, 'post', '', 4);
