(563, 3, '2012-07-05 12:56:51', '2012-07-05 12:56:51', 'We headed to Laos on the notorious "night bus".  The bus, which was to be our home for the next day and a half, was full of 30 bright red, vinyl seats which (almost) fully reclined.  The aisles were lined with neon green and orange lights, accenting the big screen t.v. at the front of the bus which played a video of barely dressed western women gyrating on stage to extremely loud electronic music. This was the luxury bus. \n\nIn the morning we arrived at the Vietnam/Laos border.  Once in Laos, the landscape changed dramatically.  The tops of the mountains were shrouded in clouds and fog. Bamboo huts dotted the high mountain passes.  The fronts of the houses abutted the road, while the backs hung off cliffs, propped up by 10 -30 foot wooden poles.  Just looking at the houses gave one a sense of vertigo. Old women walked up the steep mountain roads, carrying bags of wood, which rather than wearing across their shoulders, they strapped to their foreheads.  Families sat on their porches and chatted, drinking tea and taking in the cool mountain air.  \n\nThe ride made even the most motion-tolerant (read: me) queasy.  Weaving around mountain sides, I was glad that our driver had neglected our need to eat.  Indeed, according to road signs, in 5 1/2 hours, we went only 72 kilometers.  \n\nAs we descended from the mountains, the thatched roofs of hill villages were replaced with corrugated tin, and satellite dishes dotted each neighborhood.  The fog lifted and we entered flat (er) land. While I was somewhat saddened to leave behind these beautiful mountains, I couldn''t have been happier to move this 30 hour bus ride (which lingered in the present tense far too long) into the past.\n\nAt around 10 pm we arrived into Luang Prabang.  The sleepy town was all dark, with the exception of Phu Si hill, which juts up from the center of the city, with the golden stupa which sits at the hill''s pinnacle illuminated. \n\nLuang Prabang is situated at the confluence of the Khan and the Mekong rivers. Due to its unique architecture, history, and impressive concentration of Wats (or, temples), the city is a UNESCO world heritage site.  \n\nAlong with an Argentinean and an American (living in Indonesia) who we met on the bus ride, we searched for somewhere to lay our weary heads.  We arrived at the SySomphone guest house late.  Papa and Mama (as they prefer to be called), and their two young grandchildren welcomed us with open arms.  (Indeed, unlike in Vietnam, we found this gentle generosity to be the rule here rather than the exception). Papa and Mama headed to the kitchen to prepare us sandwiches and fresh banana and mango shakes.  Meanwhile, 3 year-old Mieu Mieu plied us with as many bananas as could fit in our stomaches, peeling the next before we had finished the last and giggling with the delight of a true hostess.  \n\nIn the morning we rented bicycles and set off to explore.  We watched as fishermen navigated the Mekong in small canoes, as monks formed a procession to collect morning alms, and as women barbecued freshly caught fish on bamboo skewers.  Gold and magenta temples, most of which were emblazoned with colorful statues of multi-headed dragons (some of which sprang forth from the heads of other dragons) densely dotted the town. \n\nWe sight-saw, got incredible $5 massages, visited markets.  And we ate.  And, boy, did we eat.  Although a week ago, we couldn''t have told you what Laotian food was, we quickly found out that Laotian food -served with wicker baskets full of sticky rice -is unbelievably delicious.  We ate steamed fish with lemongrass and chili, Laap (a salad of minced meat or tofu with onions, fish sauce, mint, roasted ground rice, and chilies), and green, yellow, and red curries with chicken and tofu.  Despite our epicurean home-runs, we also had some culinary misses, such as a papaya salad dressed with pieces of fermented crab and its juice.\n\nWe visited Tat Kuang Si, 32 km from Luang Prabang, a breathtaking multi-layered waterfall nestled in the jungle. The limestone rock turned the water from blue to bright turquoise.  We hiked up the side of the waterfall until we reached the top.  Water pooled and tumbled 100 meters down, providing a stunning view of the forest and country side.  The place was so wonderful, I was inclined to forgive even the dozens of leeches who came to call me dinner.  We spent the rest of the day swimming in the turquoise pools, and swinging from ropes suspended above the deepest of them.  \n\nWe spent another leisurely couple of days in Luang Prabang, enjoying the rain, the food, the beauty, and the people.  But, as is the rule with even the most wonderful of places when traveling, itineraries trump and the road always beckons.  So, off we were.  \n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=568><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195326.jpg" alt="20120705-195326.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=568"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195318.jpg" alt="20120705-195318.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195347.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195347.jpg" alt="20120705-195347.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Luang Prabang: where the mekong meets the khan', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '563', '', '', '2012-07-05 14:28:48', '2012-07-05 14:28:48', '', 0, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=563', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(564, 3, '2012-07-05 12:56:51', '2012-07-05 12:56:51', '', 'Auto Draft', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '563-revision', '', '', '2012-07-05 12:56:51', '2012-07-05 12:56:51', '', 563, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=564', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
