i, 32 km from Luang Prabang, a breathtaking multi-layered waterfall nestled in the jungle. The limestone rock turned the water from blue to bright turquoise.  We hiked up the side of the waterfall until we reached the top.  Water pooled and tumbled 100 meters down, providing a stunning view of the forest and country side.  The place was so wonderful, I was inclined to forgive even the dozens of leeches who came to call me dinner.  We spent the rest of the day swimming in the turquoise pools, and swinging from ropes suspended above the deepest of them.  \n\nWe spent another leisurely couple of days in Luang Prabang, enjoying the rain, the food, the beauty, and the people.  But, as is the rule with even the most wonderful of places when traveling, itineraries trump and the road always beckons.  So, off we were.  \n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195326.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195326.jpg" alt="20120705-195326.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195318.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195318.jpg" alt="20120705-195318.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195347.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120705-195347.jpg" alt="20120705-195347.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Luang Prabang: where the mekong meets the khan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '563-revision-4', '', '', '2012-07-05 13:13:03', '2012-07-05 13:13:03', '', 563, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=598', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
