(633, 1, '2012-07-10 17:29:23', '2012-07-10 17:29:23', 'After 3 liesurely days in Luang Prabang we made our way south (via back-to-back bus rides) to Tha Khaek, a small town in central Laos that sits on Laos and Thailand''s natural border, the Mekong River.  Tha Khaek is our last stop in Laos before crossing to Thailand and flying out of Bangkok.  Aside from being a convenient border crossing point into Thailand, Tha Khaek is also a good place to start a motorcycle journey to Kong Lo cave, a 7.5 km long cave only navigable by long boat located 180 km northeast of Tha Khaek by road.\n\nWe''d originally planned on doing a 400 km clockwise loop by motorcycle over 4 days (though, as we learn more and more each day, things rarely go as planned).  We over paid for a cheap, road worn Korean bike.  It had no functioning speedometer or odometer, and a fuel gauge that dropped nearly instantly from full to empty after approximately 130 km (a feature that we only discovered 130 km into our trip), but it started most of the time and looked to be in as good condition as the rest of the haggard bikes being offered so we took it.\n\nWe spent most of the first morning humming north on rte 13.  Despite being one of Laos''s major highways, we were frequently forced to slow our speed in order to navigate around the herds of cows, goats, chickens, and dogs that also used the road to get where ever they were going (or, occasionally, as a place to take a nap).  After winding our way through 40 km of mountains on rte 8 in the afternoon, we turned down a straight flat road past small villages and fields of rice paddies that stretched out to the base of the tall mountains that surrounded us.  The number of vehicles on the road decreased in inverse proportion to the number of cows, which we swirved around every few kilometers as they gave us an apathetic glare to let us know that <em>we</em> were an inconvenience to <em>them</em> and not the other way around.  The road came to a dead end at a river rushing out of the mouth of a large cave.  We''d arrived at Kong Lo.\n\nThe next morning we hired a boatman and a guide to take us the 7.5 km through the cave.  As we puttered into the cave the light from the entrance shrank to a speck until we were surrounded by darkness save for our four puny headlamps.  The cave was enormous, at points nearly to high for the light from my headlamp to reach the top.  Our boatman navigated us around the patches of water raining from the cave''s ceiling, and after 20 minutes of drifting through the darkness we pulled our boat up next to the side of the cave and our guide got out and beckoned for us to do the same.  He walked a few steps and hit a button switching on a few lights, which illuminated a couple dozen impressive stalagmites (and -tites).  We snapped a few photos, out guide hit another button to turn off the lights, we got back in the boat, and continued further into the cave.  After 40 minutes we saw another speck of light ahead and soon the cave opened up to a landscape of towering mountains poking their tops through a thin layer of white clouds.\n\nKong Lo behind us and only a day and a half into our journey, our next stop was the Nam Sanam Waterfall 40 km north of Kong Lo.  We stopped for fuel a kilometer from the trail to the waterfall.  As we pulled out of the petrol station Ali exclaimed, "Is that a monkey?  Go back!"  And, indeed, it was a monkey; a white cheeked Gibbon sitting on a stump, arms stretched behind his head lounging under an umbrella 10 meters from the gas pump.  As we approached we expected him to run, but instead he climbed to the top of his stump, scratched his head, and then lowered it in my direction as if to say "now you try".  Monkey see, monkey do...\n\nGas in our tank and monkey on our minds, we continued on the the waterfall.  We pulled our motorcycle in to the Khoun Kham village visitor center.  We were greeted by a friendly woman who told us that the waterfall was a 2 km hike from the visitor center but that the water was very high, drawing a line with her hand above her waist.  "It''s ok.  We brought our swim suits," we replied confidently.\n\nWe (Ali in particular) hike at a quick pace, and would normally knock out 2 km in 30 minutes.  But we underestimated the Laotian jungle in the rainy season.  Two minutes from the trails start, as the visitor center attendant had warned, we were up to our waists in water crossing what is probably a small ditch in the dry season.  "No problem" we said.  "We''re going to swim under the waterfall anyway."  Our naivety began to dawn on us when after wrong turns and trails lost under recently created creeks, it began to rain as we arrived at a sign indicating that we were only half way there. The finally blow to our optimism occurred when a mere hundred meters from the waterfall the trail met a river of rushing white water.  To our right was a treacherous class 6 rapid and just across the river a sign which read "You can swim" with no indication of irony.  Needless to say we were unable to swim under the waterfall (we couldn''t even get close enough to see the top).  We might have been disappointed, but the beautiful hike through the jungle was a reward in itself.  As we drove away we could see the entire mountain we''d just hiked up and caught a glimpse of the magnificent twin waterfalls that we''d only seen in part up close.\n\nWe arrived in Lak Sao (the biggest town on our journey after Tha Khaek) just after dark, ate dinner, and found the town''s only ATM.  Unfortunately the Lao Development Bank does not recognize all foreign debit cards, our included.  This may have been a matter that could have been sorted out in the bank, but we''d arrive in Lak Sao in the middle of the weekend and it wouldn''t be until monday that the bank opened.  We took stock of our assets and learned that we had just enough kip to pay for the hotel and just enough dollars and Thai baht to get us home the next day.  Fortunately even in the tiny town of Lak Sao there a people willing to give a bad exchange rate for dollars and baht seven days a week, so the next morning we paid for our hotel, exchanged money, and had a meager breakfast of fried dough balls and bananas before heading back to Tha Khaek the way we came.  Though disappointed to be cutting our trip short, the scenery on the ride up was absolutely gorgeous (particularly the mountains along rte 8), and we were happy to get a second viewing.\n\nOn a side note, Lak Sao was the half-way point of our intended loop.  We considered continuing clockwise (rather than back tracking) but had heard that the roads south of Lak Sao could be a problem if there had been a lot or rain.  Our trek to the waterfall made it clear that that there had been, and, as we were already cutting it close with gas money, we decided to play it safe and stick with familiar roads.  After returning to Tha Khaek we spoke to a mud soaked couple returning from a motorcycle trip similar to the one we had originally planned who told us that we''d made the right choice.', 'motorbike blog posts', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '631-revision-2', '', '', '2012-07-10 17:29:23', '2012-07-10 17:29:23', '', 631, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=633', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
