0120721-171832.jpg" alt="20120721-171832.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171845.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171845.jpg" alt="20120721-171845.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171857.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171857.jpg" alt="20120721-171857.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171912.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171912.jpg" alt="20120721-171912.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171905.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171905.jpg" alt="20120721-171905.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171918.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171918.jpg" alt="20120721-171918.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171940.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171940.jpg" alt="20120721-171940.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171925.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171925.jpg" alt="20120721-171925.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171946.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171946.jpg" alt="20120721-171946.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171959.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171959.jpg" alt="20120721-171959.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171952.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-171952.jpg" alt="20120721-171952.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-172006.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-172006.jpg" alt="20120721-172006.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'all the south india you can fit into 5 days.  and more.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '717-revision-4', '', '', '2012-07-21 13:22:23', '2012-07-21 13:22:23', '', 717, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=721', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(722, 1, '2012-07-21 11:38:37', '2012-07-21 11:38:37', 'From Sultan Bathery we headed to Ooty, a hill station in the tea growing mountains of Tamil Nadu.  Ooty is a popular vacation destination for Indian tourists - particularly honeymooners.  High in the Nilgiris, Ooty is a bustling and colorful city - an oasis in the undulating hills of tea and pine trees.  We arrived via a 5 hour standing-room-only bus ride which violently curved around sharp bend after sharp bend.  Only because Ooty was so beautiful did I forgive the nauseating hours during which my face was sandwiched between the odorous armpits of strangers.  \n\nAlthough we came to Ooty expecting to do some trekking, we had trouble finding anything to do there but packaged tours.  So, we spent our two days enjoying the cold, drinking absurd quantities of masala tea, and roaming the byzantine bazaar.  We met some wonderful people in and around the bazaar, developed the photos we took, and went back the next day to distribute them to our new friends.  It was a nice way to thank all those people whose faces often thanklessly dot our blog.  The one "day hike" we attempted was to the region''s highest peak - about 10km from our hotel.  Although we shared the path with menacing (and loudly honking) busses and semi-trucks, the scenery was beautiful.  However, the top of the peak wasn''t the peaceful summit we had anticipated.  Rather, it was teeming with local tourists and groups of shrieking school girls.  So, although it took us hours to climb to the peak, we didn''t linger but ten minutes at the top.\n\nWe shed our many warm layers and headed south to Kanyakumari - the southernmost tip of India.  Along the shore dozens of stalls hawk spiced mango and ice cream, tourists snap photos of the water - a confluence of three seas, and pilgrims file in to the many Hindu temples. Just off the shore, boats shuttle visitors to two impressive islets, a monument for a monk and another for a poet.  We woke up early to watch the sun rise to the sounds of blaring traditional music from two neighboring temples - a shouting contest of sorts.\n\nOff we were to our next destination:  Alleppey.  Alleppey (or Alappuzha) is the top destination for "backwater" houseboat cruises.  Although our guidebook states that while houseboat cruises "could be one of your most expensive experiences in India, it is usually worth every rupee" -- and it did cost many rupees -- we both found it relaxing but underwhelming put up against the awe inspiring beauty of Vietnam''s Ha Long Bay.  At 11am we boarded our boat, which had a beautiful front room with two day beds, 2 lounging chairs, and a table for dining.  Behind was a room with a bathroom and shower.  The boat was like a hotel on water.  There were three staff (a cook, a captain, and a third man whose duties may have only consisted of chain smoking hand rolled cigarettes on the ship''s helm) and us.  We spent the day drifting through small channels, reading D.H. Lawrence (me) and Salman Rushdie (adam),  and watching people fish, bathe, or wash their clothes on the river''s edge.  At sunset we anchored in a village that smelled of ghee sizzling in hot pans and spent some time strolling, snapping photos, and watching king fishers and giant bats fly overhead.\n\nWhen we returned to dry land 22 hours after setting sail, we hopped on a bus headed north to Kochi.  Slumped over from the oppressive heat and the weight of our ever-growing bags (I do have a soft spot for saris...), we splurged and checked-in to a "business class" hotel.  We plan to spend the next 36 hours taking hot showers, ordering room service, using wifi, and watching HBO.  A needed vacation from our vacation.... \n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-170240.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-170240.jpg" alt="20120721-170240.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'all the south india you can fit into 5 days.  and more.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '675-revision-3', '', '', '2012-07-21 11:38:37', '2012-07-21 11:38:37', '', 675, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=722', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
