 the minute we left the train station we were hounded with mobs of rickshaw drivers and shop owners with rupee signs in their eyes at the sight of tourists.  "Sir, come with me.  I will take you to a nice hotel.  Only 10 rupees".  "No, come with me.  Rooms with AC.  Veeearry cheap!".  "Please ma''am.  Come into my shop.  No need to buy.  Just have a look".  Polite no thank you''s gradually becoming stern No''s then decaying into a furrow browed, head shaking, tunnel vision quest for a clean quiet room with air conditioning.\n\nWe took shelter at Hotel Paradise, showering and basking in the AC before heading back out to make arrangements for a two and half day camel safari into the heart of the desert.  The next morning we pushed the start of our dessert trek back a few hours in order to enjoy the morning of Ali''s birthday lackadaisically with a birthday cake breakfast (Jaisalmer is not the best place to get a birthday cake btw), an ayurvedic message, and a shaded rooftop lunch.  \n\nBy the afternoon we''d taken a jeep 30 minutes southwest of Jaisalmer to meet our camels and camelman, Mr Khan.  A double seater saddle was strapped to each of our camels.  We sat in the front seat atop our bedding while our (and our camel''s) supply of food and water sat behind us.\n\nOn a whole the safari was a little miserable.  Riding a camel was far less comfortable than we had imagined, jerking us violently forward and then backwards with every step.  On days 1 and 3 we trodded past hundreds of giant windmills which, while beautiful in their own right, seemed amiss among the desert landscape.  Additionally, the hours between 10 am and 5 pm were HOT (capital H, O, and T), and midnight to 4 am, what would have otherwise been prime sleeping hours, were actually prime power generating hours with heavy winds blowing buckets of sand over us so that we became human shaped sand castle by morning.\n\nAt sundown, however, the air cooled quickly and the hours from sunset to a couple of hours after we laid down under the stars to go to sleep were warm, but pleasant.  Mr. Khan baked chapattis, boiled rice, and cooked potato curry and we ate our dinner and drank chai while we watched the round yellow sun fade away unceremoniously behind the horizon''s thick cloud of dust.', 'Western Rajasthan: some like it hot', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '768-revision-2', '', '', '2012-07-29 12:43:06', '2012-07-29 12:43:06', '', 768, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=770', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
