(776, 2, '2012-07-29 12:52:21', '2012-07-29 12:52:21', 'Having had our fill of green jungles and palm tree lined beaches, we left south India for the hotter, dryer climate of Rajasthan''s deserts.  We flew into Rajasthan''s western airport in Jodhpur, arriving in the early afternoon (the hottest time of day).  Dismayed to find that the guesthouse that we''d booked the previous week only had one air conditioned room, which was already occupied (that''ll teach us to plan ahead), we locked up our bags and made our way to Jodhpur''s main attraction, Mehrangarh, a giant fort built from the rock on which it stands towering above the rest of the city.  We made the steep climb to the top of the fort accompanied by the serenations of Jodhpur''s many street musicians bowing hand-made stringed instruments, pounding on drums, and blowing into high pitched flutes, and were rewarded with magnificent views of "the blue city" at the top.\n\nThe city''s well deserved nickname describes the color of the concrete building, a majority painted top to bottom with cheap blue paint that rubs off on your arms and legs as you pass so that newcomers, looking like blue man group rejects, are easily spotted (no pun intended).  Ali quickly became enamored with Jodhpurs colorful buildings, photogenic people, and hectic narrow streets.  Wandering around the main bazaar, we stumbled on a spice shop offering cooking classes.  We returned the next day for a six hour cooking marathon, learning how to make many of our favorite Indian dishes.  We were shown the secrets of delicious chai masala (brewed in whole milk), and cheese naan (made with yogurt rather than water), as well as given recipes and shown how to prepare palak paneer and tikka masala.  And of course we ate everything we made.  We left at midnight (two hours later than we''d planned) with bellies full and our pants tighter than when we''d arrived.\n\nThe next day we arrived in Jaisalmer, a touristy town near India''s western border with Pakistan.  From the minute we left the train station we were hounded with mobs of rickshaw drivers and shop owners with rupee signs in their eyes at the sight of tourists.  "Sir, come with me.  I will take you to a nice hotel.  Only 10 rupees".  "No, come with me.  Rooms with AC.  Veeearry cheap!".  "Please ma''am.  Come into my shop.  No need to buy.  Just have a look".  Polite no thank you''s gradually becoming stern No''s then decaying into a furrow browed, head shaking, tunnel vision quest for a clean quiet room with air conditioning.\n\nWe took shelter at Hotel Paradise, showering and basking in the AC before heading back out to make arrangements for a two and half day camel safari into the heart of the desert.  The next morning we pushed the start of our dessert trek back a few hours in order to enjoy the morning of Ali''s birthday lackadaisically with a birthday cake breakfast (Jaisalmer is not the best place to get a birthday cake btw), an ayurvedic message, and a shaded rooftop lunch.  \n\nBy the afternoon we''d taken a jeep 30 minutes southwest of Jaisalmer to meet our camels and camelman, Mr Khan.  A double seater saddle was strapped to each of our camels.  We sat in the front seat atop our bedding while our (and our camel''s) supply of food and water for the next two and a half days sat behind us.\n\nOn a whole the safari was a little miserable.  Riding a camel was far less comfortable than we had imagined, jerking us violently forward and then backwards with every step.  On days 1 and 3 we trodded past hundreds of giant windmills which, while beautiful in their own right, seemed amiss among the desert landscape.  Additionally, the hours between 10 am and 5 pm were HOT (capital H, O, and T), and midnight to 4 am, what would have otherwise been prime sleeping hours, were actually prime power generating hours with heavy winds blowing buckets of sand over us so that we became human shaped sand castles by morning.\n\nAt sundown, however, the air cooled quickly and the hours from sunset to a couple of hours after we laid down under the stars to go to sleep were warm, but pleasant.  Mr. Khan baked chapattis, boiled rice, and cooked potato curry and we ate our dinner and drank chai while we watched the round yellow sun fade away unceremoniously behind the horizon''s thick cloud of dust.\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg" alt="20120729-182155.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182149.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182149.jpg" alt="20120729-182149.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Western Rajasthan: some like it hot', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '768-revision-4', '', '', '2012-07-29 12:52:21', '2012-07-29 12:52:21', '', 768, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=776', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
