(788, 2, '2013-01-28 06:14:47', '2013-01-28 06:14:47', '<strong></strong>Having had our fill of green jungles and palm tree lined beaches, we left south India for the hotter, dryer climate of Rajasthan''s deserts. We flew into Rajasthan''s western airport in Jodhpur, arriving in the early afternoon (the hottest time of day). Dismayed to find that the guesthouse that we''d booked the previous week only had one air conditioned room, which was already occupied (that''ll teach us to plan ahead), we locked up our bags and made our way to Jodhpur''s main attraction, Mehrangarh, a giant fort built from the rock on which it stands towering above the rest of the city. We made the steep climb to the top of the fort accompanied by the serenations of Jodhpur''s many street musicians bowing hand-made stringed instruments, pounding on drums, and blowing into high pitched flutes, and were rewarded with magnificent views of "the blue city" at the top.\n\nThe city''s well deserved nickname describes the color of the concrete building, a majority painted top to bottom with cheap blue paint that rubs off on your arms and legs as you pass so that newcomers, looking like blue man group rejects, are easily spotted (no pun intended). Ali quickly became enamored with Jodhpurs colorful buildings, photogenic people, and hectic narrow streets. Wandering around the main bazaar, we stumbled on a spice shop offering cooking classes. We returned the next day for a six hour cooking marathon, learning how to make many of our favorite Indian dishes. We were shown the secrets of delicious chai masala (brewed in whole milk), and cheese naan (made with yogurt rather than water), as well as given recipes and shown how to prepare palak paneer and tikka masala. And of course we ate everything we made. We left at midnight (two hours later than we''d planned) with bellies full and our pants tighter than when we''d arrived.\n\nThe next day we arrived in Jaisalmer, a touristy town near India''s western border with Pakistan. From the minute we left the train station we were hounded with mobs of rickshaw drivers and shop owners with rupee signs in their eyes at the sight of tourists. "Sir, come with me. I will take you to a nice hotel. Only 10 rupees". "No, come with me. Rooms with AC. Veeearry cheap!". "Please ma''am. Come into my shop. No need to buy. Just have a look". Polite no thank you''s gradually becoming stern No''s then decaying into a furrow browed, head shaking, tunnel vision quest for a clean quiet room with air conditioning.\n\nWe took shelter at Hotel Paradise, showering and basking in the AC before heading back out to make arrangements for a two and half day camel safari into the heart of the desert. The next morning we pushed the start of our dessert trek back a few hours in order to enjoy the morning of Ali''s birthday lackadaisically with a birthday cake breakfast (Jaisalmer is not the best place to get a birthday cake btw), an ayurvedic message, and a shaded rooftop lunch.\n\nBy the afternoon we''d taken a jeep 30 minutes southwest of Jaisalmer to meet our camels and camelman, Mr Khan. A double seater saddle was strapped to each of our camels. We sat in the front seat atop our bedding while our (and our camel''s) supply of food and water for the next two and a half days sat behind us.\n\nOn a whole the safari was a little miserable. Riding a camel was far less comfortable than we had imagined, jerking us violently forward and then backwards with every step. On days 1 and 3 we trodded past hundreds of giant windmills which, while beautiful in their own right, seemed amiss among the desert landscape. Additionally, the hours between 10 am and 5 pm were HOT (capital H, O, and T), and midnight to 4 am, what would have otherwise been prime sleeping hours, were actually prime power generating hours with heavy winds blowing buckets of sand over us so that we became human shaped sand castles by morning.\n\nAt sundown, however, the air cooled quickly and the hours from sunset to a couple of hours after we laid down under the stars to go to sleep were warm, but pleasant. Mr. Khan baked chapattis, boiled rice, and cooked potato curry and we ate our dinner and drank chai while we watched the round yellow sun fade away unceremoniously behind the horizon''s thick cloud of dust.\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=766">Click here for more photos<img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182149.jpg" alt="20120729-182149.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg" alt="20120729-182155.jpg" /></a>', 'Western Rajasthan: some like it hot', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '768-autosave', '', '', '2013-01-28 06:14:47', '2013-01-28 06:14:47', '', 768, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=788', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(952, 2, '2012-07-14 10:29:47', '2012-07-14 10:29:47', 'We arrived into Mumbai with uncertain plans.  Although we had intended to take a train south to the southern state of Kerala directly upon arrival, we discovered that India does not make it easy for foreigners to travel by rail (or do a number of other quotidian tasks which surprisingly require proof of residency).  After days of confusion regarding how to actually book a ticket, we soon realized that we had made another mistake -- Indian trains are perpetually full.  We arrived into Mumbai "waitlisted" for the evening''s train to Kochi.  At the airport, a modest stand outfitted with an old computer running DOS and a dapper young man advertised "railway tickets" scratched on a cardboard sign.  We waited for an hour behind a frustrated French woman who couldn''t understand how ALL of the trains were booked to EVERYWHERE.  Finally, we were up. A large group of Indian men had gathered around us (Indians seem to have neither the same sense of personal space nor the same conceptions of standing in lines as do westerners).  They all put in their two cents regarding how we ought to proceed.  Wait there an hour and see what happens was the verdict.  So, we sat and watched an unnaturally large rat scurry around the arrivals area, unnoticed by passers-by.  While we finally got word that we had been moved from "waitlisted" to "confirmed", we simultaneously found out that we might not have time to actually get to the railway station before the train departed.  "How is that possible? We have over 4 hours!  The station is only 40 kilometers away!"     \n\nMumbai traffic is ugly.  An unrelenting tangled mass, spewing smog, vibrating from the cacophony of hundreds of horns, no distinguishable lanes of traffic, drivers with their feet up on the steering wheel reading the paper and spitting out large wads of red betel nut, pedestrians weaving between semi-trucks and auto-rickshaws, passing them both.  It makes L.A. freeways at rush hour look like the open road.    \n\nBy some sheer stroke of luck, we made it to the station just in time.  Our 2nd class AC berth held 6 beds.  A retired musicologist and his wife who just came from visiting their daughter, son-in-law, and two grandchildren.  A 24 year-old who met his fiancé for the first time in Mumbai (they met on a matrimony dating site for his particular caste - the warrior class, they chatted for a week, and then he had his parents arrange a marriage with her family.  they''ve been talking for a month on the phone.  he just returned from a 3 day trip to Mumbai where he first met her. he was elated. long into the evening he plied adam with questions about relationships, dating, monogamy, etc. interrupted only by frequent phone calls from his new fiancé (to whom he would whisper ''i love you, i love you, i love you'' in english).  And a philosophically oriented electrical equipment purveyor on a business trip who after 12 hours of total silence, began expounding on Hinduism:  "we and god are the same in quality, we only differ in quantity.  our souls are infinitesimally small-- 1/100,000 of the tip of a hair.  we have in fractions what krishna has in abundance.  we are a drop of water, he is the ocean".\n\nThis was India''s vibrant (and growing) middle class.  Through the 24 hour train ride, we shared food, books, and stories. drinking chai, eating biriyani, and discussing the cultural particularities and universalities of marriage, divorce, relationships, feminism, communism, education, and religion.  \n\nImmersed in a world where arranged marriages are still very much the status quo, and "dating" is something from the movies rather than reality,  they all struggled to understand the relationship between me and Adam.  The musicologist fell back on our modern day cultural equalizer: Facebook.  "Aha! You are ''In a relationship!"''  \n\nWhen the train stopped, the home-like comfort we''d created dissipated and we were back in the middle of an India whose speed was too fast and whose volume was too loud.  We spent hours walking from hotel to hotel (many of which in retrospect we assume were not hotels at all) looking for a room.  All full.  Everywhere.  Perhaps Calicut was full of Indian travelers, but without a single non-Indian face to be seen this was the moment in traveling when one begins to ask ''are we supposed to bribe someone''?\n\nWe eventually found an over-priced, musty room in a concrete building crumbling faster than it could be repaired.  At dinner people stared at us and the proprietor of the restaurant stood beside our table and watched us eat every bite.  Fortunately, every bite was delicious. It seems that westerners are still novel here in Calicut. \n\nIn the morning we took a $0.40, 4 hour local bus to Sultan Bathery which abuts a wildlife sanctuary.   The ride was beautiful (and treacherous) as we rounded hairpin bend after hairpin bend, ascending mountains until we were so far into the clouds that there was only white beyond, behind, in front and below us.  Hundreds of monkeys sat along the road side (perhaps hopeful that someone would throw out a half eaten treat?).  We entered the Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary from the southern entrance: Muthanga.    Although the experience was not comparable to our previous animal spotting experiences in Malaysia, we did see spotted deer, wild elephants, a mongoose, a sloth bear, tiger foot prints, and (as our guide called them) "common" monkeys (which we later found out to be Rhesus macaques).  \n\nAlthough we spent much of our time in southeast asia trying to veer from the "beaten path", in India we''ve hardly found a path at all.  Fortunately, surrounded by kind people, delicious food, and enough monkeys to keep us entertained, bushwhacking shouldn''t be a disappointment.\n\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=664">Click here to see more photos<img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153933.jpg" alt="20120714-153933.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153939.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153939.jpg" alt="20120714-153939.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Adam and Ali are "It''s Complicated" with India.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '646-revision-5', '', '', '2012-07-14 10:29:47', '2012-07-14 10:29:47', '', 646, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=952', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(789, 2, '2012-07-29 13:13:30', '2012-07-29 13:13:30', 'Having had our fill of green jungles and palm tree lined beaches, we left south India for the hotter, dryer climate of Rajasthan''s deserts.  We flew into Rajasthan''s western airport in Jodhpur, arriving in the early afternoon (the hottest time of day).  Dismayed to find that the guesthouse that we''d booked the previous week only had one air conditioned room, which was already occupied (that''ll teach us to plan ahead), we locked up our bags and made our way to Jodhpur''s main attraction, Mehrangarh, a giant fort built from the rock on which it stands towering above the rest of the city.  We made the steep climb to the top of the fort accompanied by the serenations of Jodhpur''s many street musicians bowing hand-made stringed instruments, pounding on drums, and blowing into high pitched flutes, and were rewarded with magnificent views of "the blue city" at the top.\n\nThe city''s well deserved nickname describes the color of the concrete building, a majority painted top to bottom with cheap blue paint that rubs off on your arms and legs as you pass so that newcomers, looking like blue man group rejects, are easily spotted (no pun intended).  Ali quickly became enamored with Jodhpurs colorful buildings, photogenic people, and hectic narrow streets.  Wandering around the main bazaar, we stumbled on a spice shop offering cooking classes.  We returned the next day for a six hour cooking marathon, learning how to make many of our favorite Indian dishes.  We were shown the secrets of delicious chai masala (brewed in whole milk), and cheese naan (made with yogurt rather than water), as well as given recipes and shown how to prepare palak paneer and tikka masala.  And of course we ate everything we made.  We left at midnight (two hours later than we''d planned) with bellies full and our pants tighter than when we''d arrived.\n\nThe next day we arrived in Jaisalmer, a touristy town near India''s western border with Pakistan.  From the minute we left the train station we were hounded with mobs of rickshaw drivers and shop owners with rupee signs in their eyes at the sight of tourists.  "Sir, come with me.  I will take you to a nice hotel.  Only 10 rupees".  "No, come with me.  Rooms with AC.  Veeearry cheap!".  "Please ma''am.  Come into my shop.  No need to buy.  Just have a look".  Polite no thank you''s gradually becoming stern No''s then decaying into a furrow browed, head shaking, tunnel vision quest for a clean quiet room with air conditioning.\n\nWe took shelter at Hotel Paradise, showering and basking in the AC before heading back out to make arrangements for a two and half day camel safari into the heart of the desert.  The next morning we pushed the start of our dessert trek back a few hours in order to enjoy the morning of Ali''s birthday lackadaisically with a birthday cake breakfast (Jaisalmer is not the best place to get a birthday cake btw), an ayurvedic message, and a shaded rooftop lunch.  \n\nBy the afternoon we''d taken a jeep 30 minutes southwest of Jaisalmer to meet our camels and camelman, Mr Khan.  A double seater saddle was strapped to each of our camels.  We sat in the front seat atop our bedding while our (and our camel''s) supply of food and water for the next two and a half days sat behind us.\n\nOn a whole the safari was a little miserable.  Riding a camel was far less comfortable than we had imagined, jerking us violently forward and then backwards with every step.  On days 1 and 3 we trodded past hundreds of giant windmills which, while beautiful in their own right, seemed amiss among the desert landscape.  Additionally, the hours between 10 am and 5 pm were HOT (capital H, O, and T), and midnight to 4 am, what would have otherwise been prime sleeping hours, were actually prime power generating hours with heavy winds blowing buckets of sand over us so that we became human shaped sand castles by morning.\n\nAt sundown, however, the air cooled quickly and the hours from sunset to a couple of hours after we laid down under the stars to go to sleep were warm, but pleasant.  Mr. Khan baked chapattis, boiled rice, and cooked potato curry and we ate our dinner and drank chai while we watched the round yellow sun fade away unceremoniously behind the horizon''s thick cloud of dust.\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=766">Click here for more photos<img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182149.jpg" alt="20120729-182149.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\n\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg" alt="20120729-182155.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Western Rajasthan: some like it hot', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '768-revision-5', '', '', '2012-07-29 13:13:30', '2012-07-29 13:13:30', '', 768, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=789', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(790, 2, '2012-07-31 14:06:39', '2012-07-31 14:06:39', '<b>UPDATE: Our <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=766">Rajasthan photo page</a> was down for a couple of days, but it''s working now so if you missed it before <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=766">go check them out</a>.</b>\r\n\r\nHaving had our fill of green jungles and palm tree lined beaches, we left south India for the hotter, dryer climate of Rajasthan''s deserts.  We flew into Rajasthan''s western airport in Jodhpur, arriving in the early afternoon (the hottest time of day).  Dismayed to find that the guesthouse that we''d booked the previous week only had one air conditioned room, which was already occupied (that''ll teach us to plan ahead), we locked up our bags and made our way to Jodhpur''s main attraction, Mehrangarh, a giant fort built from the rock on which it stands towering above the rest of the city.  We made the steep climb to the top of the fort accompanied by the serenations of Jodhpur''s many street musicians bowing hand-made stringed instruments, pounding on drums, and blowing into high pitched flutes, and were rewarded with magnificent views of "the blue city" at the top.\r\n\r\nThe city''s well deserved nickname describes the color of the concrete building, a majority painted top to bottom with cheap blue paint that rubs off on your arms and legs as you pass so that newcomers, looking like blue man group rejects, are easily spotted (no pun intended).  Ali quickly became enamored with Jodhpurs colorful buildings, photogenic people, and hectic narrow streets.  Wandering around the main bazaar, we stumbled on a spice shop offering cooking classes.  We returned the next day for a six hour cooking marathon, learning how to make many of our favorite Indian dishes.  We were shown the secrets of delicious chai masala (brewed in whole milk), and cheese naan (made with yogurt rather than water), as well as given recipes and shown how to prepare palak paneer and tikka masala.  And of course we ate everything we made.  We left at midnight (two hours later than we''d planned) with bellies full and our pants tighter than when we''d arrived.\r\n\r\nThe next day we arrived in Jaisalmer, a touristy town near India''s western border with Pakistan.  From the minute we left the train station we were hounded with mobs of rickshaw drivers and shop owners with rupee signs in their eyes at the sight of tourists.  "Sir, come with me.  I will take you to a nice hotel.  Only 10 rupees".  "No, come with me.  Rooms with AC.  Veeearry cheap!".  "Please ma''am.  Come into my shop.  No need to buy.  Just have a look".  Polite no thank you''s gradually becoming stern No''s then decaying into a furrow browed, head shaking, tunnel vision quest for a clean quiet room with air conditioning.\r\n\r\nWe took shelter at Hotel Paradise, showering and basking in the AC before heading back out to make arrangements for a two and half day camel safari into the heart of the desert.  The next morning we pushed the start of our dessert trek back a few hours in order to enjoy the morning of Ali''s birthday lackadaisically with a birthday cake breakfast (Jaisalmer is not the best place to get a birthday cake btw), an ayurvedic message, and a shaded rooftop lunch.  \r\n\r\nBy the afternoon we''d taken a jeep 30 minutes southwest of Jaisalmer to meet our camels and camelman, Mr Khan.  A double seater saddle was strapped to each of our camels.  We sat in the front seat atop our bedding while our (and our camel''s) supply of food and water for the next two and a half days sat behind us.\r\n\r\nOn a whole the safari was a little miserable.  Riding a camel was far less comfortable than we had imagined, jerking us violently forward and then backwards with every step.  On days 1 and 3 we trodded past hundreds of giant windmills which, while beautiful in their own right, seemed amiss among the desert landscape.  Additionally, the hours between 10 am and 5 pm were HOT (capital H, O, and T), and midnight to 4 am, what would have otherwise been prime sleeping hours, were actually prime power generating hours with heavy winds blowing buckets of sand over us so that we became human shaped sand castles by morning.\r\n\r\nAt sundown, however, the air cooled quickly and the hours from sunset to a couple of hours after we laid down under the stars to go to sleep were warm, but pleasant.  Mr. Khan baked chapattis, boiled rice, and cooked potato curry and we ate our dinner and drank chai while we watched the round yellow sun fade away unceremoniously behind the horizon''s thick cloud of dust.\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=766">Click here for more photos<img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182149.jpg" alt="20120729-182149.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120729-182155.jpg" alt="20120729-182155.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Western Rajasthan: some like it hot', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '768-revision-6', '', '', '2012-07-31 14:06:39', '2012-07-31 14:06:39', '', 768, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=790', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
