areas turning the once quiet town of Leh into a city so loud and chaotic that it began to resemble the rest of India.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=821">click here to see photos from Ladakh<img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100832.jpg" alt="20120808-100832.jpg" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100925.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100925.jpg" alt="20120808-100925.jpg" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100919.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100919.jpg" alt="20120808-100919.jpg" /></a>', 'Ladakh: It''s All Downhill From Here', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '826-revision-11', '', '', '2012-09-06 00:18:43', '2012-09-06 00:18:43', '', 826, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=931', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(860, 3, '2012-08-19 22:36:39', '2012-08-19 22:36:39', 'After the cool mountain air and restful pace of Ladakh, we headed southeast to our penultimate destination: the holy city of Varanasi. We arrived before 5:30 am via a flight from Leh and overnight train from Delhi. The city still slept, wrapped in its own filth which wouldn''t be swept aside or washed away until its denizens awoke hours later. Stray dogs, holy cows, and troops of monkeys pilfered through trash which filled the street and poured over into shop openings and houses'' stoops. Narrow roads (barely large enough for you and the truculent bovine who seems pleased to scoot closer to you, bang you into a wall, and then swat you with its fecal-ful tail) wind around brightly colored buildings, so serpentine that after an hour one is left dismayed as to how she''s returned to where she began.\r\n\r\nVaranasi is a city of profound religious import, said to have been founded by the Hindu God, Lord Shiva 3,000 years ago (placing it as a contender for the oldest continuously habitated city in the world). Hindus believe it is a place where Moksha (or, the "final release" from the chain of reincarnation) may be achieved. They also believe that the river Ganges represents (and for some sects, IS) the goddess Shakti, and that bathing in her waters erases all sins and purifies the soul. Varanasi is also a pilgrimage site for Buddhists as it is believed that it was here that Siddhartha Gautama gave his first sermon to his disciples, making it the birthplace of Buddhism.\r\n\r\nThis is a city where pilgrims sit on the ubiquitous mats of priests (whose holy credibility might be called in to question by the sheer quantity of them) to have their palms read and their fortunes deciphered. A city where under every arm there is a water bottle filled with the murky brown water of the Ganges, a souvenir to bring home. A city where monkeys roam freely through the temples, filching bags of food and screeching at devotees.\r\n\r\nHere, life centers around the approximately one hundred ghats (or, broad flights of stairs that connect the city to the river''s waters) which lead worshippers down to the holy Ganges river. There are ghats for every purpose: holy bathing, performing the puja, and even two specifically for cremations. We spent the day roaming these ghats, ambivalent about the crush of sound, color, and smells. Then, drenched in sweat and looking for some creature comforts, we hired a bicycle rickshaw driver to take us on a 3 hour tour of the city (the going rate: 40 rupees/ $0.80 an hour).\r\n\r\nAfter dinner, we wandered through the maze north, hoping to find the funeral ghats. The small cobbled stone alleyways were pitch black with the only light escaping from the small doors of houses, where families huddled together around shared dinner plates. We finally smelled smoke, and soon enough we were standing on the bank of the river, surrounded by walls of large logs used to fuel the cremation fires. This ghat - Manikarnika - draws devout hindus from across India (and beyond) to burn their loved ones above the Ganges river, hoping that such an auspicious passing will allow their souls to escape the cycle of reincarnation and ascend into a heavenly realm. There were nearly a dozen fires roaring. Male family members dressed in all white and prayed around the fires, watching the smoke, perhaps wondering if somewhere in the grey cloud was the soul of the person they loved.  We looked on in awe for hours, feeling like interlopers but too moved, too curious to leave.\r\n\r\nAccording to a man we met, the cremation fires roar all day and all night, totaling about 200 cremations per day. When the body is burned (which takes approximately 3 hours), the family gathers up the bones and ash and throws them into the Ganges. However, because wood is expensive, some families cannot afford to fully burn their dead, leaving large pieces of bodies to float in the river. Additionally, women who are pregnant, children, those with leprosy, and those who died of snake bites are never burned (as it is thought that they have not yet completed a full life and thus must come back into the world and try again) and instead are tied to large rocks and thrown whole into the river. As a result (rumor has it), the local authorities began breeding and training flesh-eating turtles to consume the decomposing bodies which had begun to pose a threat to public health.\r\n\r\nThen on to our final destination: the Taj Mahal. While neither of us was too excited to battle the heat, crowds, and hustlers of Agra (a notoriously terrible city to visit), no visit to India would be complete without it. Although Indians pay 20 rupees to gain entrance into the monument, foreign visitors pay 750 rupees ($15 USD, about the price of a hotel room with air conditioning for the night). The Taj Mahal was built in the early 1600''s by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan as a monument to his love for his 2nd (of 3) wife (Mumtaz Mahal) who died delivering her 14th child. The mausoleum was constructed with beautiful white marble, with ruby, jade, turquoise, lapis lazuli, sapphire, and onyx inlaid into the marble as flowers and Koranic text. Up close, the tomb comes alive with color.\r\n\r\nThus, having closed our time in India with the most quintessentially Indian tourist experience, we began our 5 day journey home. And so ends our 22 flight, 10 country, 11 week adventure.  Thanks for reading!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=882">Click here to see photos from Varanasi and Agra<img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120819-192825.jpg" alt="20120819-192825.jpg" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120819-192121.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120819-192121.jpg" alt="20120819-192121.jpg" /></a>', '22 flights, 10 countries, and 11 weeks later', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '22-flights-10-countries-and-11-weeks-later', '', '', '2013-01-28 06:23:13', '2013-01-28 06:23:13', '', 0, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=860', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(859, 2, '2012-08-08 17:19:11', '2012-08-08 17:19:11', 'In the early hours of July 30th Ali and I were sound asleep in a hotel room in Delhi when we were awoken by a loud pop and looked up to see that the air conditioning unit mounted on the wall above our bed was off.  Having suffered through many similar events since arriving in India, we sighed disappointingly and dozed off again.  Cities across India lose power daily - typically for several hours at a time.  Though, in most cases, "lose" is the wrong word.  It seems more often it''s the case that the power is turned off strategically in order to avoid grid overloads.  In Rajasthan while waiting to patronize an internet cafe during a power outage, we asked someone when the electricity might come back on and he replied, "whenever the powermen decide to turn it back on".  On the morning of July 30th, however, powermen across India seemed uncoordinated as Ali and I unknowingly became participants in a series of power outages which affected half of India''s population and more than 9% of the world''s population (yeah, there''s a lot of people in India).  Half an hour later we were in a taxi on our way to the Delhi airport.  The power was still out across the country, but our driver soared through intersections once regulated by traffic lights using only his horn to let other vehicles know that, in his opinion, he had the right away.  Luckily traffic was light at 3:30 in the morning and we arrived at the airport with out a problem.  \r\n\r\nWe''d been in this same airport just a week earlier during a layover en route to Jodhpur.  Surprisingly, despite lack of grid power, the airport was operating much the same as the previous week.  Ticket counters were still printing tickets, televisions screens were still displaying departures and arrivals (most on time), and McDonald''s was still serving non-beef, non-pork burgers and breakfast sandwiches.  As it turns out, the Indira Gandhi Airport boasts one of the world''s largest diesel powered generators, and within seconds of the outage 90% of the airport facilities were back up and functioning normally.  Despite the unprecedented outage, the cogs that keep Delhi in motion continued to turn.  The city was so unphased by the historical event that it wasn''t until a week later when checking emails for the first time since the outage that, by family inquiries about whether we were alright, we knew that anything out of the ordinary had happened at all.\r\n\r\nOur plane was on the ground in Leh, a peaceful city tucked deep in the Himalayan Mountains, before the rush hour chaos due to lack of power in Delhi began.  Leh is the capital of Ladakh, a region in India''s northern most state, Jamu & Kashmir.  Ladakh is unlike the rest of India in almost every way.  The majority of India is either Hindu or Muslim, while Ladakh, which takes in many Tibetan refugees (and whose culture, food, dress, and language seems indistinguishable from Tibet''s), is predominantly Budhist.  The streets of most Indian cities are a chaotic mess of busses, cars, motorcycles, and people all pushing to the front of an endless sea of bodies and horns.  Leh''s streets, while busy with shops and restaurants, are peaceful and horn-free with vehicles respecting single file lanes, traffic signs, and pedestrian spaces.  And while Ladakh, like Rajasthan, is technically a desert, the landscape is composed of beautiful snow capped mountains below crystal blue skies, and the towns, through carefully constructed irrigation systems, are lush green oasises in the valleys of barren mountains.  Finally, while the rest of India is either sweltering or scorching hot in the summer, Leh, nestled high in the Himalayan Mountains, has light-jacket weather in the mornings and evenings and shorts and t-shirt weather in the afternoons.\r\n\r\nLadakh''s altitude has disadvantages as well.  Sea-level dwellers commonly experience headaches, nausea, dizziness, and feel like complete wimps when walking up small hills.  We spent the morning and early afternoon of our first day rearranging our train and flight schedule to accommodate a 5 day trek from Lamayuru to Chilling ending with a whitewater rafting trip down the Zanskar River.  By pushing back our return flight to Delhi we were able to start the trek 2 days later, giving me much needed time to adjust to the altitude and recover from the debilitating symptoms of altitude sickness.\r\n\r\nEarly on August 1st my headache and lightheadedness had subsided, and my blue lips regained their pinkish hue (though Ali and I were still getting winded walking up even modest hills).  A taxi drove Ali, me, our friend Natalie, and our trekking guide the four hours along the motion sickness inducing, half-finished road from Leh to Lamayuru to start our trek.  The two days of rest before starting our trek were essential, but several more would have been better.  As a result of a decrease in air density, the available amount of oxygen to sustain normal mental and physiological activity decreases around 3000 m.  High altitude is defined as 1500 m to 3500 m and very high altitude as 3500 m to 5500 m.  Lamayuru sits at 3400 m (a mile higher than Denver Colorado), and on several occasions the trek took us over mountain passes of nearly 5000 m (over 3 miles above sea level).\r\n\r\nThe first two days were relatively easy (and I must emphasize that this is <em>relative</em> to days 3 and 4).  Lamayuru, where we began our trek, is a small town with a beautiful monastery high in the hills.  Around the monastery, old men and women sit spinning handheld prayer wheels, while Tibetan prayer flags flap in the wind, carrying away prayers into the air.  Each night of the trek we slept in homes in villages along the way with the amount of walking each day determined by the distances between adjacent villages.  Not a problem for days 1 and 2.  Lamayuru is only a 4 hour hike to Wanla and Wanla only a 6 hour hike to Hinju.  But Sumdho Chinmu, the next village beyond Hinju is a 12 hour hike separated by a 4950 m mountain pass.  Halfway up the mountain our pace abruptly slowed.  We''d take a hundred small steps before becoming completely out of breath (read: unable to breathe), necessitating frequent stops to sit on the path, catch our breath, and wait for the lightheadedness lessen.  As we climbed higher on the steep and narrow mountain-side path, a hundred steps between stops shrank to 50, then 25.  As we increased out altitude our step sizes became smaller and the number of steps between stops decreased as the amount of oxygen we were able to suck into our lungs gradually decreased with each step forward.  For both of us, the experience was frustrating, and hands-down one of the most challenging physical feats of our lives. Once at the top we collapsed and closed our eyes for half an hour before continuing on to Sumdho Chinmu (luckily most of the 5+ hour descent was downhill).  We arrived after 6 in the evening and went straight to bed.\r\n\r\nThe next day was similar in length and difficulty.  Though we climbed two passes on the fourth day, the higher of the two was a mere 4700 m.  Whether it was the 10 hours of sleep, an extra day of aclimitisation, or that our tallest ascent was 250 m less high than the previous day''s, the 4th day seemed significantly easier than the previous.  And though difficult, days 3 and 4 were also beautiful.  The views from atop the passes were remarkable.  Surrounded by white topped mountains and hills of red and green rocks, we enjoyed a near infinite view of the foliaged valleys far below.\r\n\r\nOn day 4 we made a 1500 m (approximately 1 mile) descent from the day''s second pass to Chilling, a village on the Zanskar River.  The descent was epic with some mountains resembling a lunar landscape, and others the sinister jagged rocked Mordor. The next morning we put aside our hiking boots and walking sticks in exchange for wet suits and paddles and started down the Zanskar.  The rapids seemed mild, but the water, which originates from the snow capped mountains that surround the river, was as ice cold as the glacier it started from.  Natalie and I sat in the front and were perpetually soaked with the bone chilling glacial water.  Half way down the river we pulled ashore for a break and Natalie, who had had enough cold water for the day, gave up her spot in the front to an Austrian man convinced that living in the alps made him a better candidate for the position.  Within 5 minutes of casting off again a rapid tilted our raft throwing our Austrian friend (and most of the rest of the boat) into the icy grey water.  We were able to pull everyone back into the boat within a minute, but the fellow from Austria spent the rest of the trip down the river shivering and making good natured comments through clenched teeth about how much colder it was in the front of the raft\r\n\r\nCold, wet, and utterly exhausted, we returned to Leh.  We decided to spend some time looking for a hotel with hot water (something that our previous hotel hadn''t).  We walked from hotel to hotel, confused by the near ubiquitous "no vacancy".  Indeed, something about Leh had changed while we were high in the mountain passes.  The streets were jammed packed with cars, westerners, and a proliferation of scarlet and saffron clad monks.  It took us only a few minutes to realize that Leh had doubled in size due to a five day visit from the Dalai Lama.  \r\n\r\nThe next day we got a taxi early in the morning to drive us the 9 km to the monastery where the Dalai Lama would be speaking.  Ladakh''s tranquility was replaced with carnivalesque excitement and the frenetic energy of thousands of people all trying to snag a good seat.   The Dalai Lama made jokes, gave suggestions on improved monastic pedagogy, and even kicked out a monk in the front row who he chided for "not paying attention".  More impressive than his holiness''s words, however, were the thousands of men, women, and children flooding in from surrounding areas turning the once quiet town of Leh into a city so loud and chaotic that it began to resemble the rest of India.<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100832.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100832.jpg" alt="20120808-100832.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100925.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100925.jpg" alt="20120808-100925.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100919.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120808-100919.jpg" alt="20120808-100919.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Ladakh: It''s All Downhill From Here', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '826-revision-9', '', '', '2012-08-08 17:19:11', '2012-08-08 17:19:11', '', 826, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=859', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(862, 3, '2012-08-19 23:36:39', '2012-08-19 23:36:39', 'After the cool mountain air and restful pace of Ladakh, we headed southeast to our penultimate destination: the holy city of Varanasi.  We arrived before 5:30 am via a flight from Leh and overnight train from Delhi. The city still slept, wrapped in its own filth which wouldn''t be swept aside or washed away until its denizens awoke hours later.  Stray dogs, holy cows, and troops of monkeys pilfered through trash which filled the street and poured over into shop openings and houses'' stoops.  Narrow roads (barely large enough for you and the truculent bovine who seems pleased to scoot closer to you, bang you into a wall, and then swat you with its fecal-ful tail) wind around brightly colored buildings, so serpentine that after an hour one is left dismayed as to how  she''s returned to where she began.  \n\nVaranasi is a city of profound religious import, said to have been founded by the Hindu God, Lord Shiva 3,000 years ago (placing it as a contender for the oldest continuously habitated city in the world).  Hindus believe it is a place where Moksha (or, the "final release" from the chain of reincarnation) may be achieved.  They also believe that the river Ganges represents (and for some sects, IS) the goddess Shakti, and that bathing in her waters erases all sins and purifies the soul. Varanasi is also a pilgrimage site for Buddhists as it is believed that it was here that Siddhartha Gautama gave his first sermon to his disciples, making it the birthplace of Buddhism. \n\nHere, life centers around the approximately one hundred ghats (or, broad flights of stairs that connect the city to the river''s waters) which lead worshippers down to the holy Ganges river.  There are ghats for every purpose: holy bathing, performing the puja, and even two specifically for cremations.  \n\nThis is a city where pilgrims sit on the ubiquitous mats of priests (whose holy credibility might be called in to question by the sheer quantity of them) to have their palms read and their fortunes deciphered.  A city where under every arm there is a water bottle filled with the murky brown water of the Ganges, a souvenir to bring home. A city where monkeys roam freely through the temples, filching bags of food and screeching at devotees. \n\nWe spent the day roaming these ghats, ambivalent about the crush of sound, color, and smells.  Then, drenched in sweat and looking for some creature comforts, we hired a bicycle rickshaw driver to take us on a 3 hour tour of the city (the going rate: 40 rupees/ $0.80 an hour). \n\nAfter dinner, we wandered through the maze north, hoping to find the funeral ghats.  The small cobbled stone alleyways were pitch black with the only light escaping from the small doors of houses, where families huddled together around shared dinner plates. We finally smelled smoke, and soon enough we were standing on the bank of the river, surrounded by walls of large logs used to fuel the cremation fires.  This ghat - Manikarnika draws devout hindus from across India (and beyond) to burn their loved ones above the Ganges river, hoping that such an auspicious passing will allow their souls to escape the cycle of reincarnation and ascend into a heavenly realm. There were nearly a dozen fires roaring.  Male family members dressed in all white and prayed around the fires, watching the smoke, perhaps wondering if somewhere in the grey cloud was the soul of the person they loved.  \n\nAccording to a man we met, the cremation fires roar all day and all night, totaling about 200 cremations per day.  When the body is burned (which takes approximately 3 hours), the family gathers up the bones and ash and throws them into the Ganges.  However, because wood is expensive, some families cannot afford to fully burn their dead, leaving large pieces of bodies to float in the river.  Additionally, women who are pregnant, children, those with leprosy, and those who died of snake bites are never burned (as it is thought that they have not yet completed a full life and thus must come back into the world and try again) and instead are tied to large rocks and thrown whole into the river.  As a result (rumor has it), the local authorities began breeding and training flesh-eating turtles to consume the decomposing bodies which had begun to pose a threat to public health.  And we bathed in that river.  shudder. \n\nThen on to our final destination: the Taj Mahal.  While neither of us was too excited to battle the heat, crowds, and hustlers of Agra (a notoriously terrible city to visit), no visit to India would be complete without it. Although Indians pay 20 rupees to gain entrance into the monument, foreign visitors pay 750 rupees ($15 USD, about the price of a hotel room with air conditioning for the night).  The Taj Mahal was built in the early 1600''s by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan as a monument to his love for his 2nd (of 3) wife (Mumtaz Mahal) who died delivering her 14th child.  The mausoleum was constructed with beautiful white marble, with ruby, jade, turquoise, lapis lazuli, sapphire, and onyx inlaid into the marble as flowers and Koranic text. Up close, the tomb comes alive with color.\n\nThus, having closed our time in India with the most quintessentially Indian tourist experience, we began our 5 day journey home.  And so ends our 22 flight, 10 country, 11 week adventure.', '22 flights, 10 countries, and 11 weeks later', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '860-revision-2', '', '', '2012-08-19 23:36:39', '2012-08-19 23:36:39', '', 860, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=862', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
