(955, 2, '2012-07-02 01:01:26', '2012-07-02 01:01:26', 'According to Vietnamese legend, a giant dragon once lived in the mountains on the northern coast of Vietnam.  As it flew down the mountain to dive into the sea, its tail bounced along the tops of the hills carving out steep canyons leading into the ocean.  As the pockets left by the dragon''s tail filled with shimmering emerald green water from the Gulf of Tonkin, it created a bay so magical that it gives even the most ardent skeptic pause to contemplate his disbelief in myths upon seeing its beauty.  This is Halong Bay (literally, where the dragon descends into the sea).\n\nWe did little planning before leaving the States, but everything we saw and read convinced us to put Halong Bay on our list of places we had to see in Southeast Asia.  However, after a negative experience on Khao San road in Bangkok (hoards of irreverent westerners whose overwhelming presence destroyed nearly all traces of authentic Thai culture) we''d decided we needed to make an effort to stray from the beaten paths suggested by most travel guide books.  We''d heard that boat tours out of Halong City, while beautiful, are tarnished by both trash in the water and carts of Asian kitsch being sold to the bus loads of western tourists.\n\nWe decided instead to launch our exploration of Halong Bay and its equally beautiful neighbor, Lan Ha Bay, from the less easily accessible town of Cat Ba, located on an island in the southern part of Halong Bay.  Once in Cat Ba we booked an overnight boat tour of the Bay leaving the following morning.\n\nAt 8 am we took a short bus ride to the port of departure and boarded our boat, a motorized junk with sleeping quarters, a bathroom, and a kitchen on the bottom level and an area for lounging, dining, and playing cards on the top level.  Our crew consisted of a driver, a cook, and a "tour guide" (who spent 75% of the trip sleeping), and we were joined by three additional passengers, a group of travelers in their 20s from New Zealand.\n\nAs we left the crowded fishing port, we began to pass small islands of limestone rock, partially covered by green vegetation, jutting more than 100 m straight out of the water.  The bay is densely populated with these limeston monuments, some like tall buildings, others like fortress walls.\n\nAfter a few hours of cruising through the bay and snapping picture after picture that we knew couldn''t do it justice, we stopped at one of the larger islands, climbed a few dozen stairs half way to the top and found a cave illuminated by generator powered lights.  50 m in, the cave opened again to the outside revealing a gigantic pool of still green water completely surrounded by a ring of towering limestone.\n\nThe rest of the two days wast spent eating delicious freshly caught sea food, napping and reading on the top deck, escaping the heat with plunges into the ocean, and exploring more caves and secluded pools and beaches by kayak.  In the evening after our first day on the water, the air had cooled and the sky was clear.  We pulled down the sheet which had provided shade in the heat of the day and dragged a couple of mattresses from the sleeping quarters to the top deck, laid on our backs and fell asleep looking for shooting stars.\n\n<br /><br />\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=487">click to see more photos</a>\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=487"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235342.jpg" alt="20120701-235342.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235350.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120701-235350.jpg" alt="20120701-235350.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Ha Long: where the dragon descends into the sea', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '490-revision-13', '', '', '2012-07-02 01:01:26', '2012-07-02 01:01:26', '', 490, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=955', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(956, 2, '2012-08-25 05:05:20', '2012-08-25 05:05:20', 'After the cool mountain air and restful pace of Ladakh, we headed southeast to our penultimate destination: the holy city of Varanasi. We arrived before 5:30 am via a flight from Leh and overnight train from Delhi. The city still slept, wrapped in its own filth which wouldn''t be swept aside or washed away until its denizens awoke hours later. Stray dogs, holy cows, and troops of monkeys pilfered through trash which filled the street and poured over into shop openings and houses'' stoops. Narrow roads (barely large enough for you and the truculent bovine who seems pleased to scoot closer to you, bang you into a wall, and then swat you with its fecal-ful tail) wind around brightly colored buildings, so serpentine that after an hour one is left dismayed as to how she''s returned to where she began.\r\n\r\nVaranasi is a city of profound religious import, said to have been founded by the Hindu God, Lord Shiva 3,000 years ago (placing it as a contender for the oldest continuously habitated city in the world). Hindus believe it is a place where Moksha (or, the "final release" from the chain of reincarnation) may be achieved. They also believe that the river Ganges represents (and for some sects, IS) the goddess Shakti, and that bathing in her waters erases all sins and purifies the soul. Varanasi is also a pilgrimage site for Buddhists as it is believed that it was here that Siddhartha Gautama gave his first sermon to his disciples, making it the birthplace of Buddhism.\r\n\r\nThis is a city where pilgrims sit on the ubiquitous mats of priests (whose holy credibility might be called in to question by the sheer quantity of them) to have their palms read and their fortunes deciphered. A city where under every arm there is a water bottle filled with the murky brown water of the Ganges, a souvenir to bring home. A city where monkeys roam freely through the temples, filching bags of food and screeching at devotees.\r\n\r\nHere, life centers around the approximately one hundred ghats (or, broad flights of stairs that connect the city to the river''s waters) which lead worshippers down to the holy Ganges river. There are ghats for every purpose: holy bathing, performing the puja, and even two specifically for cremations. We spent the day roaming these ghats, ambivalent about the crush of sound, color, and smells. Then, drenched in sweat and looking for some creature comforts, we hired a bicycle rickshaw driver to take us on a 3 hour tour of the city (the going rate: 40 rupees/ $0.80 an hour).\r\n\r\nAfter dinner, we wandered through the maze north, hoping to find the funeral ghats. The small cobbled stone alleyways were pitch black with the only light escaping from the small doors of houses, where families huddled together around shared dinner plates. We finally smelled smoke, and soon enough we were standing on the bank of the river, surrounded by walls of large logs used to fuel the cremation fires. This ghat - Manikarnika - draws devout hindus from across India (and beyond) to burn their loved ones above the Ganges river, hoping that such an auspicious passing will allow their souls to escape the cycle of reincarnation and ascend into a heavenly realm. There were nearly a dozen fires roaring. Male family members dressed in all white and prayed around the fires, watching the smoke, perhaps wondering if somewhere in the grey cloud was the soul of the person they loved.  We looked on in awe for hours, feeling like interlopers but too moved, too curious to leave.\r\n\r\nAccording to a man we met, the cremation fires roar all day and all night, totaling about 200 cremations per day. When the body is burned (which takes approximately 3 hours), the family gathers up the bones and ash and throws them into the Ganges. However, because wood is expensive, some families cannot afford to fully burn their dead, leaving large pieces of bodies to float in the river. Additionally, women who are pregnant, children, those with leprosy, and those who died of snake bites are never burned (as it is thought that they have not yet completed a full life and thus must come back into the world and try again) and instead are tied to large rocks and thrown whole into the river. As a result (rumor has it), the local authorities began breeding and training flesh-eating turtles to consume the decomposing bodies which had begun to pose a threat to public health.\r\n\r\nThen on to our final destination: the Taj Mahal. While neither of us was too excited to battle the heat, crowds, and hustlers of Agra (a notoriously terrible city to visit), no visit to India would be complete without it. Although Indians pay 20 rupees to gain entrance into the monument, foreign visitors pay 750 rupees ($15 USD, about the price of a hotel room with air conditioning for the night). The Taj Mahal was built in the early 1600''s by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan as a monument to his love for his 2nd (of 3) wife (Mumtaz Mahal) who died delivering her 14th child. The mausoleum was constructed with beautiful white marble, with ruby, jade, turquoise, lapis lazuli, sapphire, and onyx inlaid into the marble as flowers and Koranic text. Up close, the tomb comes alive with color.\r\n\r\nThus, having closed our time in India with the most quintessentially Indian tourist experience, we began our 5 day journey home. And so ends our 22 flight, 10 country, 11 week adventure.  Thanks for reading!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=882">Click here to see photos from Varanasi and Agra<img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120819-192825.jpg" alt="20120819-192825.jpg" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120819-192121.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/20120819-192121.jpg" alt="20120819-192121.jpg" /></a>', '22 flights, 10 countries, and 11 weeks later', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '860-revision-8', '', '', '2012-08-25 05:05:20', '2012-08-25 05:05:20', '', 860, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=956', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
