(959, 2, '2012-06-27 04:44:16', '2012-06-27 04:44:16', 'After taking in as much marine life as our novice lungs could take, we migrated inward from the coast to the jungle, the river Kinabatangan.  Borneo is home to one of the oldest rainforests in the world which in turn houses many endangered, beautiful, and (in the spirit of full disclosure) somewhat homely creatures.  \r\n\r\nWe traveled to Kota Kinabatangan and after various forms of transportation we finally arrived at our lodge, nestled under the jungle''s towering canopy.  We started our day there with a "river cruise" where our guide navigated a small boat up and down the big brown river.  Seconds after we began, as is the way in the rainforest, a torrential downpour began.  Despite the sheets of water tumbling into our boat, within minutes we happened upon a troop of <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-164455.jpg" alt="20120626-164455.jpg"> proboscis monkeys </a>.  The proboscis monkeys, whose name in Malay means "Dutchman" -- a less than flattering reference to the noses and bellies of their colonizers, lounged in big trees right on the river bank.  When we caught their gaze, they were sure to turn their backs to us as if trying to avoid the snickers that their bulbous noses and overgrown bellies provoke.  \r\n\r\nAs we continued down river, we saw a magnificent <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-175851.jpg"> pygmy elephant</a> eating leaves on the water''s edge.  I was aggravated with our guide, Helson, who hardly slowed the boat as we passed by.  But, he knew what he was doing.  Where there''s one elephant, there are more.  Just around the bend, 6 adult, 2 adolescent, and 2 newborn elephants bathed in mud on the river banks.  We pulled up, and sat in awed silence mere feet from the creatures (whose name "pygmy" doesn''t do justice to their enormity).   So impressed with the experience, I was sure that the next 3 days would be a let-down.  What could possibly live up to seeing a pack of wild elephants (and wild baby elephants at that!)  so close-up? \r\n\r\nYet, the jungle was literally shaking with life. everywhere you looked leaves and branches were swaying, bending, and sometimes breaking under the weight of monkeys fighting, grooming, playing, and satisfying other less polite urges. Birds flew overhead, and the jungle resonated with the sounds of frogs and cicadas and the smell of wild boar.\r\n\r\nThe next two days were filled with treks in the jungle and cruises down the river filled with wildlife.  We saw wild boars, <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-180347.jpg"> pig-tailed macaques </a>, <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-180355.jpg"> long-tailed macaques </a>, <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-175331.jpg"> rhino hornbills </a>, and eagles.  Once the sun went down, the jungle transformed -- a veritable changing of the guard.  Birds, monkeys, and elephants settled in for the night, and snakes, crocodiles, bats, and other carnivores claimed the jungle as their own. During night hikes adam''s extensive childhood training in snake hunting payed off -- he spotted a slug eating snake which impressed even our guide.  We also saw birds sleeping on their nests, impressively large insects, and even a <a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-175059.jpg"> Malay civet </a>(which adam was convinced was just a house cat gone feral in the jungle).  \r\n\r\nOn our last full day, after a long hike, we put our feet in a lake, only to be swarmed by thousands upon thousands of small fish, devouring the bacteria and dead skin from hands and feet.  We were told that people PAY for this kind of treatment in European spas: "it''s exfoliating"..."really brings you back to nature".  Ick. \r\n\r\nDuring a sunset trip down the river the night before we left, we all silently hoped to see the elusive, endangered orangutan (which in Malay means "man of the forest").  And -- remarkably-- we did.  Two black masses silhouetted in the heights of a fig tree slowly began to move.  And move closer.  Soon, we could make out a mom and her child, leisurely spanning out their seemingly indeterminable limbs to grab figs and pop them one by one into their mouths.  The sun began to set, and we watched as the orangutans climbed out of the fig tree and into the tree directly in front of us in order to construct a nest where they''d pass the night.  Branch by branch, the nest was made.  And soon they tucked themselves in for the night.  And so, contented and covered in scabs from leeches and patches of mud, we did the same.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=460">click here to see more photos</a>\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=460"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111552.jpg" alt="20120627-111552.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111605.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120627-111605.jpg" alt="20120627-111605.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'sometimes you eat the fish.  sometimes the fish eat you.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '429-revision-14', '', '', '2012-06-27 04:44:16', '2012-06-27 04:44:16', '', 429, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=959', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(961, 2, '2012-07-21 15:10:32', '2012-07-21 15:10:32', 'From Sultan Bathery we headed to Ooty, a hill station in the tea growing mountains of Tamil Nadu.  Ooty is a popular vacation destination for Indian tourists - particularly honeymooners.  High in the Nilgiris, Ooty is a bustling and colorful city - an oasis in the undulating hills of tea and pine trees.  We arrived via a 5 hour standing-room-only bus ride which violently curved around sharp bend after sharp bend.  Only because Ooty was so beautiful did I forgive the nauseating hours during which my face was sandwiched between the odorous armpits of strangers.  \n\nAlthough we came to Ooty expecting to do some trekking, we had trouble finding anything to do there but packaged tours.  So, we spent our two days enjoying the cold, drinking absurd quantities of masala tea, and roaming the byzantine bazaar.  We met some wonderful people in and around the bazaar, developed the photos we took, and went back the next day to distribute them to our new friends.  It was a nice way to thank all those people whose faces often thanklessly dot our blog.  The one "day hike" we attempted was to the region''s highest peak - about 10km from our hotel.  Although we shared the path with menacing (and loudly honking) busses and semi-trucks, the scenery was beautiful.  However, the top of the peak wasn''t the peaceful summit we had anticipated.  Rather, it was teeming with local tourists and groups of shrieking school girls.  So, although it took us hours to climb to the peak, we didn''t linger but ten minutes at the top.\n\nWe shed our many warm layers and headed south to Kanyakumari - the southernmost tip of India.  Along the shore dozens of stalls hawk spiced mango and ice cream, tourists snap photos of the water - a confluence of three seas, and pilgrims file in to the many Hindu temples. Just off the shore, boats shuttle visitors to two impressive islets, a monument for a monk and another for a poet.  We woke up early to watch the sun rise to the sounds of blaring traditional music from two neighboring temples - a shouting contest of sorts.\n\nOff we were to our next destination:  Alleppey.  Alleppey (or Alappuzha) is the top destination for "backwater" houseboat cruises.  Although our guidebook states that while houseboat cruises "could be one of your most expensive experiences in India, it is usually worth every rupee" -- and it did cost many rupees -- we both found it relaxing but underwhelming put up against the awe inspiring beauty of Vietnam''s Ha Long Bay.  At 11am we boarded our boat, which had a beautiful front room with two day beds, 2 lounging chairs, and a table for dining.  Behind was a room with a bathroom and shower.  The boat was like a hotel on water.  There were three staff (a cook, a captain, and a third man whose duties may have only consisted of chain smoking hand rolled cigarettes on the ship''s helm) and us.  We spent the day drifting through small channels, reading D.H. Lawrence (me) and Salman Rushdie (adam),  and watching people fish, bathe, or wash their clothes on the river''s edge.  At sunset we anchored in a village that smelled of ghee sizzling in hot pans and spent some time strolling, snapping photos, and watching king fishers and giant bats fly overhead.\n\nWhen we returned to dry land 22 hours after setting sail, we hopped on a bus headed north to Kochi.  Slumped over from the oppressive heat and the weight of our ever-growing bags (I do have a soft spot for saris...), we splurged and checked-in to a "business class" hotel.  We plan to spend the next 36 hours taking hot showers, ordering room service, using wifi, and watching HBO.  A needed vacation from our vacation.... \n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=717">click here for more photos<img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-170240.jpg" alt="20120721-170240.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-204025.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120721-204025.jpg" alt="20120721-204025.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'all the south india you can fit into 5 days.  and more.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '675-revision-5', '', '', '2012-07-21 15:10:32', '2012-07-21 15:10:32', '', 675, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=961', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(962, 2, '2013-01-28 06:15:54', '2013-01-28 06:15:54', 'We arrived into Mumbai with uncertain plans. Although we had intended to take a train south to the southern state of Kerala directly upon arrival, we discovered that India does not make it easy for foreigners to travel by rail (or do a number of other quotidian tasks which surprisingly require proof of residency). After days of confusion regarding how to actually book a ticket, we soon realized that we had made another mistake -- Indian trains are perpetually full. We arrived into Mumbai "waitlisted" for the evening''s train to Kochi. At the airport, a modest stand outfitted with an old computer running DOS and a dapper young man advertised "railway tickets" scratched on a cardboard sign. We waited for an hour behind a frustrated French woman who couldn''t understand how ALL of the trains were booked to EVERYWHERE. Finally, we were up. A large group of Indian men had gathered around us (Indians seem to have neither the same sense of personal space nor the same conceptions of standing in lines as do westerners). They all put in their two cents regarding how we ought to proceed. Wait there an hour and see what happens was the verdict. So, we sat and watched an unnaturally large rat scurry around the arrivals area, unnoticed by passers-by. While we finally got word that we had been moved from "waitlisted" to "confirmed", we simultaneously found out that we might not have time to actually get to the railway station before the train departed. "How is that possible? We have over 4 hours! The station is only 40 kilometers away!"\r\n\r\nMumbai traffic is ugly. An unrelenting tangled mass, spewing smog, vibrating from the cacophony of hundreds of horns, no distinguishable lanes of traffic, drivers with their feet up on the steering wheel reading the paper and spitting out large wads of red betel nut, pedestrians weaving between semi-trucks and auto-rickshaws, passing them both. It makes L.A. freeways at rush hour look like the open road.\r\n\r\nBy some sheer stroke of luck, we made it to the station just in time. Our 2nd class AC berth held 6 beds. A retired musicologist and his wife who just came from visiting their daughter, son-in-law, and two grandchildren. A 24 year-old who met his fiancé for the first time in Mumbai (they met on a matrimony dating site for his particular caste - the warrior class, they chatted for a week, and then he had his parents arrange a marriage with her family. they''ve been talking for a month on the phone. he just returned from a 3 day trip to Mumbai where he first met her. he was elated. long into the evening he plied adam with questions about relationships, dating, monogamy, etc. interrupted only by frequent phone calls from his new fiancé (to whom he would whisper ''i love you, i love you, i love you'' in english). And a philosophically oriented electrical equipment purveyor on a business trip who after 12 hours of total silence, began expounding on Hinduism: "we and god are the same in quality, we only differ in quantity. our souls are infinitesimally small-- 1/100,000 of the tip of a hair. we have in fractions what krishna has in abundance. we are a drop of water, he is the ocean".\r\n\r\nThis was India''s vibrant (and growing) middle class. Through the 24 hour train ride, we shared food, books, and stories. drinking chai, eating biriyani, and discussing the cultural particularities and universalities of marriage, divorce, relationships, feminism, communism, education, and religion.\r\n\r\nImmersed in a world where arranged marriages are still very much the status quo, and "dating" is something from the movies rather than reality, they all struggled to understand the relationship between me and Adam. The musicologist fell back on our modern day cultural equalizer: Facebook. "Aha! You are ''In a relationship!"''\r\n\r\nWhen the train stopped, the home-like comfort we''d created dissipated and we were back in the middle of an India whose speed was too fast and whose volume was too loud. We spent hours walking from hotel to hotel (many of which in retrospect we assume were not hotels at all) looking for a room. All full. Everywhere. Perhaps Calicut was full of Indian travelers, but without a single non-Indian face to be seen this was the moment in traveling when one begins to ask ''are we supposed to bribe someone''?\r\n\r\nWe eventually found an over-priced, musty room in a concrete building crumbling faster than it could be repaired. At dinner people stared at us and the proprietor of the restaurant stood beside our table and watched us eat every bite. Fortunately, every bite was delicious. It seems that westerners are still novel here in Calicut.\r\n\r\nIn the morning we took a $0.40, 4 hour local bus to Sultan Bathery which abuts a wildlife sanctuary. The ride was beautiful (and treacherous) as we rounded hairpin bend after hairpin bend, ascending mountains until we were so far into the clouds that there was only white beyond, behind, in front and below us. Hundreds of monkeys sat along the road side (perhaps hopeful that someone would throw out a half eaten treat?). We entered the Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary from the southern entrance: Muthanga. Although the experience was not comparable to our previous animal spotting experiences in Malaysia, we did see spotted deer, wild elephants, a mongoose, a sloth bear, tiger foot prints, and (as our guide called them) "common" monkeys (which we later found out to be Rhesus macaques).\r\n\r\nAlthough we spent much of our time in southeast asia trying to veer from the "beaten path", in India we''ve hardly found a path at all. Fortunately, surrounded by kind people, delicious food, and enough monkeys to keep us entertained, bushwhacking shouldn''t be a disappointment.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=664">Click here to see more photos<img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153933.jpg" alt="20120714-153933.jpg" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153939.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153939.jpg" alt="20120714-153939.jpg" /></a>', 'Adam and Ali are "It''s Complicated" with India.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '646-revision-6', '', '', '2013-01-28 06:15:54', '2013-01-28 06:15:54', '', 646, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=962', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
