/a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153939.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/20120714-153939.jpg" alt="20120714-153939.jpg" /></a>', 'Adam and Ali are "It''s Complicated" with India.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '646-autosave', '', '', '2013-02-02 19:23:54', '2013-02-02 19:23:54', '', 646, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=963', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(964, 2, '2012-07-01 17:27:28', '2012-07-01 17:27:28', 'A sleepless night of packing, followed by two consecutive nights of dozing  in airports and planes, we arrived in Mumbai exhausted in the early evening of our third full day of traveling.  We splurged and spent an extra $2 on a taxi with AC.  Worth every rupee.  The hour long ride to our hotel  was both dreadful and amazing.  Five lanes of cars, motorbikes, and autorickshaws, all pushing their way down a three lane road, making their presence known with a near constant buzz of their horns.  With automobiles so tightly packed, I could have, at any time, reached over and honked the horn of the car next to us.  Please keep your arms in the vehicle at all times.  If you want to keep them that is.  After depositing our packs at the Royal Castle Hotel, we went out to take in the city.  Mumbai is fantastic.  Vibrant, dirty, teaming with people, and nearly apathetic of our existence.\n\nToday we awoke early (unable to sleep due to jet lag) and did a bit more roaming, looking for something delicious for breakfast and a strong cup of coffee.  Afterwards we packed up our belongings and grabbed a taxi to the India Guest House in Colaba.  The 20 minute, un-air conditioned ride made me glad we''d opted for AC on the previous day.  After checking in, we again hit the city, wandering past the famous Taj Mahal Hotel and into the Gateway of India where we arranged for a taxi to drive us to all of the obligatory tourist stops: Dhobi Ghaat, open air laundry; Worli Fishing Village; Mani Bhavan Gandhi Museum; etc...  We came back to the hotel early and took a long, much need nap, before heading out for our first true Indian dining experience.  Paneer Tikka Masala for me and Vegetable Korma for Ali.  Absolutely delicious.\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231052.jpg" alt="20120604-231052.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231101.jpg" alt="20120604-231101.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231109.jpg" alt="20120604-231109.jpg" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=153"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120604-231115.jpg" alt="20120604-231115.jpg" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162322.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162322.jpg" alt="20120606-162322.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162331.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120606-162331.jpg" alt="20120606-162331.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153524.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153524.jpg" alt="20120626-153524.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'india is great.  horn ok please.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '176-revision-11', '', '', '2012-07-01 17:27:28', '2012-07-01 17:27:28', '', 176, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=964', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(965, 2, '2012-07-01 17:28:21', '2012-07-01 17:28:21', 'We arrived early Saturday morning, unprepared for what was in store.  The airport was tiny, reflecting the 17 year-long tourism boycott which ended only two years ago.  At the airport we were met by men wearing longyi --long traditional skirts, and women whose entire faces were painted yellow.  Initially I thought it was for the benefit of tourists, a kitschy show of traditional culture. Turns out, unlike most countries where men wear western clothing while women are the carriers of culture, in Myanmar it is the men who wear traditional clothing while women dress in imported Chinese blouses and skirts.  The women, however, don''t pass as entirely western.  Women and children paint large circles, intricate lines, or entire masks of  tha nap khar, a yellowish paste made from wood, on their faces.  \n\nWe soon discovered that Myanmar does not accept cards.  No one.  No where. None whatsoever.  One must exchange precious US dollars.  And not just any dollars. Myanmar does not accept bills more than six years old, torn, worn, folded, or otherwise show any sign of use.  Myanmar apparently also has a delusional conception of their currency''s worth.  At the airport, government registered money changers offer an exchange rate of $1 USD for 8 Kyat, while just outside the airport doors the "black-market" offers 840 Kyat for $1 USD.   So, we scrounged together whatever we had, using heavy books and moist towels in a true mafioso fashion to turn our crumpled, old dollars into something acceptable to the street-corner, back-door money changers.   Alas.  We largely failed.  \n\nIn our two days in Yangon, we could count all the westerners we saw on our fingers.  Due to the bad international press, heavy travel restrictions, and difficulty obtaining a visa, only the most intrepid travelers, or those anxious to escape the heavily trodden backpacker circuit of southeast asia, make their way to Myanmar.  Billboards dot the country which read "Myanmar welcomes and takes care of tourists".  This is a message that the people have truly taken to heart.    There is little to no haggling on price.  We never felt taken advantage of, preyed upon, extorted or otherwise abused here. While I risk making absurd generalizations that no population could live up to, our impression was  that Burmese people are open, honest, generous with their time, and curious about us.  Every person we passed greeted us with a wave and a large smile, little kids ran up to dole out high fives, and mothers encouraged their toddlers to blow kisses at us.  Really a refreshing change of pace for the calloused traveler, always on guard, always cynical.  \n\nWe could also count all of the overt signs of a military presence: Zero. For a country known internationally for a military that abuses, rapes, murders, silences, and systematically strips away rights from its people, the strong arm of the state was illusive. Most shops openly posted photographs of Aung San Suu Kyi, who, likened to Nelson Mandela and having received the Nobel Peace Prize,  is a national hero and represents hope for political reform.  We even witnessed a protest.  At Shwedagon Paya, a large (and astoundingly beautiful) temple complex in the center of the city, Buddhist monks (who have historically been loud and visible in their dissent against the government) and lay people from Rakhin state condemned the government for not protecting its people from politically and religiously motivated acts of violence (allegedly) committed by Bangladeshis on the two nations'' border.   \n\nAlong with being on the front line for political reform, monks, clad in flowing red robes, continued to shatter our preconceptions of serene, docile, and otherworldly beings.  In Myanmar,which is described as the most devout Buddhist country in the world, all boys and men are expected to shave their heads, don robes, and pick up alms bowls at least twice in their lives, once in boyhood, and once after becoming a man.  As a result, the line between monks and lay people is fuzzy.  Many monks smoke cigarettes, are covered in tattoos, and spend their days watching soccer and eating snacks with their buddies.  It took us a long time to become accustomed to the sight of a monk reclining at a street-side cafe, eating peanuts and giggling with friends.    Yes, perhaps I could be a monk when I grow up...\n<br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/?page_id=234"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120613-124624.jpg" alt="20120613-124624.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a><br /><br /><a href="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153659.jpg"><img src="http://anywherethewindblows.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/20120626-153659.jpg" alt="20120626-153659.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>', 'Hello Burma! Or should I call you Myanmar?...', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '228-revision-6', '', '', '2012-07-01 17:28:21', '2012-07-01 17:28:21', '', 228, 'http://anywherethewindblows.com/?p=965', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
